        {
            "Original": "This document defines several changes that optionally affect implementations of TLS 1.2, including those which do not also support TLS 1.3: \\- A version downgrade protection mechanism is described inSection 4.1.3.",
            "Adjusted": "This document defines several changes that optionally affect implementations of TLS 1.2, including those which do not also support TLS 1.3. A version downgrade protection mechanism is described in Section 4.1.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- RSASSA-PSS signature schemes are defined in Section 4.2.3.",
            "Adjusted": "RSASSA-PSS signature schemes are defined in Section 4.2.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The \"supported_versions\" ClientHello extension can be used to negotiate the version of TLS to use, in preference to the legacy_version field of the ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "The \"supported_versions\" ClientHello extension can be used to negotiate the version of TLS to use, in preference to the legacy_version field of the ClientHello."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The \"signature_algorithms_cert\" extension allows a client to indicate which signature algorithms it can validate in X.509 certificates.",
            "Adjusted": "The \"signature_algorithms_cert\" extension allows a client to indicate which signature algorithms the client can validate in X.509 certificates."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additionally, this document clarifies some compliance requirements for earlier versions of TLS; see Section 9.3.",
            "Adjusted": "Additionally, this document clarifies some compliance requirements for earlier versions of TLS; see Section 9.3."
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.1. Conventions and:
{
    "1. Introduction -> 1.1. Conventions and Terminology": [
        {
            "Original": "The key words \"MUST\", \"MUST NOT\", \"REQUIRED\", \"SHALL\", \"SHALL NOT\", \"SHOULD\", \"SHOULD NOT\", \"RECOMMENDED\", \"NOT RECOMMENDED\", \"MAY\", and \"OPTIONAL\" in this document are to be interpreted as described inBCP 14 [RFC2119] [RFC8174] when, and only when, they appear in all capitals, as shown here.",
            "Adjusted": "The key words \"MUST\", \"MUST NOT\", \"REQUIRED\", \"SHALL\", \"SHALL NOT\", \"SHOULD\", \"SHOULD NOT\", \"RECOMMENDED\", \"NOT RECOMMENDED\", \"MAY\", and \"OPTIONAL\" in this document are to be interpreted as described in BCP 14 [RFC2119] [RFC8174] when, and only when, the key words appear in all capitals, as shown here."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The following terms are used: client: The endpoint initiating the TLS connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "connection: A transport-layer connection between two endpoints.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "endpoint: Either the client or server of the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "handshake: An initial negotiation between client and server that establishes the parameters of their subsequent interactions within TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "peer: An endpoint.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When discussing a particular endpoint, \"peer\" refers to the endpoint that is not the primary subject of discussion.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "receiver: An endpoint that is receiving records.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "sender: An endpoint that is transmitting records.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "server: The endpoint that did not initiate the TLS connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

