4. Handshake Protocol:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol": [
        {
            "Original": "The handshake protocol is used to negotiate the security parameters of a connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Handshake messages are supplied to the TLS record layer, where they are encapsulated within one or more TLSPlaintext or TLSCiphertext structures which are processed and transmitted as specified by the current active connection state.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "enum { client_hello(1), server_hello(2), new_session_ticket(4), end_of_early_data(5), encrypted_extensions(8), certificate(11), certificate_request(13), certificate_verify(15), finished(20), key_update(24), message_hash(254), (255) } HandshakeType; struct { HandshakeType msg_type; /* handshake type */ uint24 length; /* remaining bytes in message */ select (Handshake.msg_type) { case client_hello: ClientHello; case server_hello: ServerHello; case end_of_early_data: EndOfEarlyData; case encrypted_extensions: EncryptedExtensions; case certificate_request: CertificateRequest; case certificate: Certificate; case certificate_verify: CertificateVerify; case finished: Finished; case new_session_ticket: NewSessionTicket; case key_update: KeyUpdate; }; } Handshake; Protocol messages MUST be sent in the order defined in Section 4.4.1 and shown in the diagrams in Section 2.",
            "Adjusted": "The handshake protocol defines an enumeration of handshake types including client_hello, server_hello, new_session_ticket, end_of_early_data, encrypted_extensions, certificate, certificate_request, certificate_verify, finished, key_update, and message_hash. A handshake structure contains the message type, length, and a selection of message content based on the type. Protocol messages must be sent in the order defined in Section 4.4.1 and shown in the diagrams in Section 2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A peer which receives a handshake message in an unexpected order MUST abort the handshake with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "New handshake message types are assigned by IANA as described in Section 11.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

3. Presentation Language -> 3.4. Vectors:
{
    "3.4. Vectors": [
        {
            "Original": "A vector (single-dimensioned array) is a stream of homogeneous data elements.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The size of the vector may be specified at documentation time or left unspecified until runtime.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In either case, the length declares the number of bytes, not the number of elements, in the vector.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The syntax for specifying a new type, T', that is a fixed- length vector of type T is T T'[n]; Here, T' occupies n bytes in the data stream, where n is a multiple of the size of T.",
            "Adjusted": "The syntax for specifying a new type, T', that is a fixed-length vector of type T is T T'[n]; Here, T' occupies n bytes in the data stream, where n is a multiple of the size of T."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length of the vector is not included in the encoded stream.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the following example, Datum is defined to be three consecutive bytes that the protocol does not interpret, while Data is three consecutive Datum, consuming a total of nine bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "opaque Datum[3]; /* three uninterpreted bytes */ Datum Data[9]; /* three consecutive 3-byte vectors */ Variable-length vectors are defined by specifying a subrange of legal lengths, inclusively, using the notation <floor..ceiling>.",
            "Adjusted": "Variable-length vectors are defined by specifying a subrange of legal lengths, inclusively, using the notation <floor..ceiling>."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When these are encoded, the actual length precedes the vector's contents in the byte stream.",
            "Adjusted": "When variable-length vectors are encoded, the actual length precedes the vector's contents in the byte stream."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length will be in the form of a number consuming as many bytes as required to hold the vector's specified maximum (ceiling) length.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A variable-length vector with an actual length field of zero is referred to as an empty vector.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "T T'<floor..ceiling>; In the following example, \"mandatory\" is a vector that must contain between 300 and 400 bytes of type opaque.",
            "Adjusted": "In the following example, \"mandatory\" is a vector that must contain between 300 and 400 bytes of type opaque."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It can never be empty.",
            "Adjusted": "The mandatory vector can never be empty."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The actual length field consumes two bytes, a uint16, which is sufficient to represent the value 400 (see Section 3.3).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Similarly, \"longer\" can represent up to 800 bytes of data, or 400 uint16 elements, and it may be empty.",
            "Adjusted": "Similarly, \"longer\" can represent up to 800 bytes of data, or 400 uint16 elements, and the longer vector may be empty."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Its encoding will include a two-byte actual length field prepended to the vector.",
            "Adjusted": "The encoding of the longer vector will include a two-byte actual length field prepended to the vector."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length of an encoded vector must be an exact multiple of the length of a single element (e.g., a 17-byte vector of uint16 would be illegal).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "opaque mandatory<300..400>; /* length field is two bytes, cannot be empty */ uint16 longer<0..800>; /* zero to 400 16-bit unsigned integers */",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Protocol Overview -> 2.3. 0-RTT Data:
{
    "2. Protocol Overview -> 2.3. 0-RTT Data": [
        {
            "Original": "When clients and servers share a PSK (either obtained externally or via a previous handshake), TLS 1.3 allows clients to send data on the first flight (\"early data\").",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client uses the PSK to authenticate the server and to encrypt the early data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As shown in Figure 4, the 0-RTT data is just added to the 1-RTT handshake in the first flight.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The rest of the handshake uses the same messages as for a 1-RTT handshake with PSK resumption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Client Server ClientHello \\+ early_data \\+ key_share* \\+ psk_key_exchange_modes \\+ pre_shared_key (Application Data*) --------> ServerHello \\+ pre_shared_key \\+ key_share* {EncryptedExtensions} \\+ early_data* {Finished} <\\-------- [Application Data*] (EndOfEarlyData) {Finished} --------> [Application Data] <\\-------> [Application Data] \\+ Indicates noteworthy extensions sent in the previously noted message.",
            "Adjusted": "The client sends a ClientHello with early_data, key_share, psk_key_exchange_modes, and pre_shared_key extensions, along with optional Application Data. The server responds with a ServerHello containing pre_shared_key and key_share extensions, followed by EncryptedExtensions with early_data, and Finished. The client then sends EndOfEarlyData and Finished, after which both parties exchange Application Data. The plus symbol indicates noteworthy extensions sent in the previously noted message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* Indicates optional or situation-dependent messages/extensions that are not always sent.",
            "Adjusted": "The asterisk indicates optional or situation-dependent messages or extensions that are not always sent."
        },
        {
            "Original": "() Indicates messages protected using keys derived from a client_early_traffic_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "Parentheses indicate messages protected using keys derived from a client_early_traffic_secret."
        },
        {
            "Original": "{} Indicates messages protected using keys derived from a [sender]_handshake_traffic_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "Curly braces indicate messages protected using keys derived from a sender_handshake_traffic_secret."
        },
        {
            "Original": "[] Indicates messages protected using keys derived from [sender]_application_traffic_secret_N.",
            "Adjusted": "Square brackets indicate messages protected using keys derived from sender_application_traffic_secret_N."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Figure 4: Message Flow for a 0-RTT Handshake IMPORTANT NOTE: The security properties for 0-RTT data are weaker than those for other kinds of TLS data.",
            "Adjusted": "The security properties for 0-RTT data are weaker than those for other kinds of TLS data."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specifically: 1\\.",
            "Adjusted": "Specifically, first:"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This data is not forward secret, as it is encrypted solely under keys derived using the offered PSK.",
            "Adjusted": "0-RTT data is not forward secret, as it is encrypted solely under keys derived using the offered PSK."
        },
        {
            "Original": "2\\.",
            "Adjusted": "Second:"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There are no guarantees of non-replay between connections.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Protection against replay for ordinary TLS 1.3 1-RTT data is provided via the server's Random value, but 0-RTT data does not depend on the ServerHello and therefore has weaker guarantees.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is especially relevant if the data is authenticated either with TLS client authentication or inside the application protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "This weakness is especially relevant if the data is authenticated either with TLS client authentication or inside the application protocol."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The same warnings apply to any use of the early_exporter_master_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "0-RTT data cannot be duplicated within a connection (i.e., the server will not process the same data twice for the same connection), and an attacker will not be able to make 0-RTT data appear to be 1-RTT data (because it is protected with different keys).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Appendix E.5 contains a description of potential attacks, and Section 8 describes mechanisms which the server can use to limit the impact of replay.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Protocol Overview -> 2.2. Resumption:
{
    "2. Protocol Overview -> 2.2. Resumption and Pre-Shared Key (PSK)": [
        {
            "Original": "Although TLS PSKs can be established out of band, PSKs can also be established in a previous connection and then used to establish a new connection (\"session resumption\" or \"resuming\" with a PSK).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once a handshake has completed, the server can send the client a PSK identity that corresponds to a unique key derived from the initial handshake (seeSection 4.6.1).",
            "Adjusted": "Once a handshake has completed, the server can send the client a PSK identity that corresponds to a unique key derived from the initial handshake (see Section 4.6.1)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client can then use that PSK identity in future handshakes to negotiate the use of the associated PSK.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server accepts the PSK, then the security context of the new connection is cryptographically tied to the original connection and the key derived from the initial handshake is used to bootstrap the cryptographic state instead of a full handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS 1.2 and below, this functionality was provided by \"session IDs\" and \"session tickets\" [RFC5077 Session Resumption without Server-Side State\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "In TLS 1.2 and below, this functionality was provided by \"session IDs\" and \"session tickets\" [RFC5077 Session Resumption without Server-Side State]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both mechanisms are obsoleted in TLS 1.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "PSKs can be used with (EC)DHE key exchange in order to provide forward secrecy in combination with shared keys, or can be used alone, at the cost of losing forward secrecy for the application data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Figure 3 shows a pair of handshakes in which the first handshake establishes a PSK and the second handshake uses it: Client Server Initial Handshake: ClientHello \\+ key_share --------> ServerHello \\+ key_share {EncryptedExtensions} {CertificateRequest*} {Certificate*} {CertificateVerify*} {Finished} <\\-------- [Application Data*] {Certificate*} {CertificateVerify*} {Finished} --------> <\\-------- [NewSessionTicket] [Application Data] <\\-------> [Application Data] Subsequent Handshake: ClientHello \\+ key_share* \\+ pre_shared_key --------> ServerHello \\+ pre_shared_key \\+ key_share* {EncryptedExtensions} {Finished} <\\-------- [Application Data*] {Finished} --------> [Application Data] <\\-------> [Application Data] Figure 3: Message Flow for Resumption and PSK As the server is authenticating via a PSK, it does not send a Certificate or a CertificateVerify message.",
            "Adjusted": "Figure 3 shows a pair of handshakes in which the first handshake establishes a PSK and the second handshake uses the PSK. As the server is authenticating via a PSK, it does not send a Certificate or a CertificateVerify message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a client offers resumption via a PSK, it SHOULD also supply a \"key_share\" extension to the server to allow the server to decline resumption and fall back to a full handshake, if needed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server responds with a \"pre_shared_key\" extension to negotiate the use of PSK key establishment and can (as shown here) respond with a \"key_share\" extension to do (EC)DHE key establishment, thus providing forward secrecy.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When PSKs are provisioned out of band, the PSK identity and the KDF hash algorithm to be used with the PSK MUST also be provisioned.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: When using an out-of-band provisioned pre-shared secret, a critical consideration is using sufficient entropy during the key generation, as discussed in [RFC4086].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
