1. Introduction -> 1.2. Major Difference:
{
    "1.2. Major Differences from TLS 1.2": [
        {
            "Original": "The following is a list of the major functional differences between TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is not intended to be exhaustive, and there are many minor differences.",
            "Adjusted": "The list is not intended to be exhaustive, and there are many minor differences."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The list of supported symmetric encryption algorithms has been pruned of all algorithms that are considered legacy.",
            "Adjusted": "The list of supported symmetric encryption algorithms has been pruned of all algorithms that are considered legacy."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Those that remain are all Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data (AEAD) algorithms.",
            "Adjusted": "The algorithms that remain are all Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data (AEAD) algorithms."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The cipher suite concept has been changed to separate the authentication and key exchange mechanisms from the record protection algorithm (including secret key length) and a hash to be used with both the key derivation function and handshake message authentication code (MAC).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- A zero round-trip time (0-RTT) mode was added, saving a round trip at connection setup for some application data, at the cost of certain security properties.",
            "Adjusted": "A zero round-trip time (0-RTT) mode was added, saving a round trip at connection setup for some application data, at the cost of certain security properties."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Static RSA and Diffie-Hellman cipher suites have been removed; all public-key based key exchange mechanisms now provide forward secrecy.",
            "Adjusted": "Static RSA and Diffie-Hellman cipher suites have been removed; all public-key based key exchange mechanisms now provide forward secrecy."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- All handshake messages after the ServerHello are now encrypted.",
            "Adjusted": "All handshake messages after the ServerHello are now encrypted."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The newly introduced EncryptedExtensions message allows various extensions previously sent in the clear in the ServerHello to also enjoy confidentiality protection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The key derivation functions have been redesigned.",
            "Adjusted": "The key derivation functions have been redesigned."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The new design allows easier analysis by cryptographers due to their improved key separation properties.",
            "Adjusted": "The new design allows easier analysis by cryptographers due to the improved key separation properties of the key derivation functions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The HMAC-based Extract-and-Expand Key Derivation Function (HKDF) is used as an underlying primitive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The handshake state machine has been significantly restructured to be more consistent and to remove superfluous messages such as ChangeCipherSpec (except when needed for middlebox compatibility).",
            "Adjusted": "The handshake state machine has been significantly restructured to be more consistent and to remove superfluous messages such as ChangeCipherSpec (except when needed for middlebox compatibility)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Elliptic curve algorithms are now in the base spec, and new signature algorithms, such as EdDSA, are included.",
            "Adjusted": "Elliptic curve algorithms are now in the base spec, and new signature algorithms, such as EdDSA, are included."
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS 1.3 removed point format negotiation in favor of a single point format for each curve.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Other cryptographic improvements were made, including changing the RSA padding to use the RSA Probabilistic Signature Scheme (RSASSA-PSS), and the removal of compression, the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA), and custom Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE) groups.",
            "Adjusted": "Other cryptographic improvements were made, including changing the RSA padding to use the RSA Probabilistic Signature Scheme (RSASSA-PSS), and the removal of compression, the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA), and custom Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (DHE) groups."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The TLS 1.2 version negotiation mechanism has been deprecated in favor of a version list in an extension.",
            "Adjusted": "The TLS 1.2 version negotiation mechanism has been deprecated in favor of a version list in an extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This increases compatibility with existing servers that incorrectly implemented version negotiation.",
            "Adjusted": "The version list in an extension increases compatibility with existing servers that incorrectly implemented version negotiation."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Session resumption with and without server-side state as well as the PSK-based cipher suites of earlier TLS versions have been replaced by a single new PSK exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "Session resumption with and without server-side state as well as the PSK-based cipher suites of earlier TLS versions have been replaced by a single new PSK exchange."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- References have been updated to point to the updated versions of RFCs, as appropriate (e.g., RFC 5280 rather than RFC 3280).",
            "Adjusted": "References have been updated to point to the updated versions of RFCs, as appropriate (e.g., RFC 5280 rather than RFC 3280)."
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction:
{
    "1. Introduction": [
        {
            "Original": "The primary goal of TLS is to provide a secure channel between two communicating peers; the only requirement from the underlying transport is a reliable, in-order data stream.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specifically, the secure channel should provide the following properties: \\- Authentication: The server side of the channel is always authenticated; the client side is optionally authenticated.",
            "Adjusted": "Specifically, the secure channel should provide the following properties: Authentication: The server side of the channel is always authenticated; the client side is optionally authenticated."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Authentication can happen via asymmetric cryptography (e.g., RSA [RSA], the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) [ECDSA\"\")], or the Edwards-Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (EdDSA) [RFC8032\"\")]) or a symmetric pre-shared key (PSK).",
            "Adjusted": "Authentication can happen via asymmetric cryptography (e.g., RSA, the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA), or the Edwards-Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (EdDSA)) or a symmetric pre-shared key (PSK)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Confidentiality: Data sent over the channel after establishment is only visible to the endpoints.",
            "Adjusted": "Confidentiality: Data sent over the channel after establishment is only visible to the endpoints."
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS does not hide the length of the data it transmits, though endpoints are able to pad TLS records in order to obscure lengths and improve protection against traffic analysis techniques.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Integrity: Data sent over the channel after establishment cannot be modified by attackers without detection.",
            "Adjusted": "Integrity: Data sent over the channel after establishment cannot be modified by attackers without detection."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These properties should be true even in the face of an attacker who has complete control of the network, as described in [RFC3552].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Appendix E for a more complete statement of the relevant security properties.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS consists of two primary components: \\- A handshake protocol (Section 4) that authenticates the communicating parties, negotiates cryptographic modes and parameters, and establishes shared keying material.",
            "Adjusted": "TLS consists of two primary components: A handshake protocol (Section 4) that authenticates the communicating parties, negotiates cryptographic modes and parameters, and establishes shared keying material."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The handshake protocol is designed to resist tampering; an active attacker should not be able to force the peers to negotiate different parameters than they would if the connection were not under attack.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- A record protocol (Section 5) that uses the parameters established by the handshake protocol to protect traffic between the communicating peers.",
            "Adjusted": "A record protocol (Section 5) that uses the parameters established by the handshake protocol to protect traffic between the communicating peers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The record protocol divides traffic up into a series of records, each of which is independently protected using the traffic keys.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS is application protocol independent; higher-level protocols can layer on top of TLS transparently.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The TLS standard, however, does not specify how protocols add security with TLS; how to initiate TLS handshaking and how to interpret the authentication certificates exchanged are left to the judgment of the designers and implementors of protocols that run on top of TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document defines TLS version 1.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "While TLS 1.3 is not directly compatible with previous versions, all versions of TLS incorporate a versioning mechanism which allows clients and servers to interoperably negotiate a common version if one is supported by both peers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document supersedes and obsoletes previous versions of TLS, including version 1.2 [RFC5246 Protocol Version 1.2\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "This document supersedes and obsoletes previous versions of TLS, including version 1.2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It also obsoletes the TLS ticket mechanism defined in [RFC5077 Session Resumption without Server-Side State\"\")] and replaces it with the mechanism defined in Section 2.2.",
            "Adjusted": "This document also obsoletes the TLS ticket mechanism defined in RFC5077 and replaces the TLS ticket mechanism with the mechanism defined in Section 2.2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because TLS 1.3 changes the way keys are derived, it updates [RFC5705\"\")] as described in Section 7.5.",
            "Adjusted": "Because TLS 1.3 changes the way keys are derived, TLS 1.3 updates RFC5705 as described in Section 7.5."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It also changes how Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) messages are carried and therefore updates [RFC6066 Extensions: Extension Definitions\"\")] and obsoletes [RFC6961 Multiple Certificate Status Request Extension\"\")] as described in Section 4.4.2.1.",
            "Adjusted": "TLS 1.3 also changes how Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) messages are carried and therefore updates RFC6066 and obsoletes RFC6961 as described in Section 4.4.2.1."
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4.2.6. Post-Handshake Client Authentication": [
        {
            "Original": "The \"post_handshake_auth\" extension is used to indicate that a client is willing to perform post-handshake authentication (Section 4.6.2).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST NOT send a post-handshake CertificateRequest to clients which do not offer this extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
