            "Adjusted": "The PostHandshakeAuth structure is empty, and the extension_data field of the post_handshake_auth extension has zero length."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.4. Certificate Authorities": [
        {
            "Original": "The \"certificate_authorities\" extension is used to indicate the certificate authorities (CAs) which an endpoint supports and which SHOULD be used by the receiving endpoint to guide certificate selection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The body of the \"certificate_authorities\" extension consists of a CertificateAuthoritiesExtension structure.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "opaque DistinguishedName<1..2^16-1>; struct { DistinguishedName authorities<3..2^16-1>; } CertificateAuthoritiesExtension; authorities: A list of the distinguished names [X501] of acceptable certificate authorities, represented in DER-encoded [X690, Canonical Encoding Rules \\(CER\\) and Distinguished Encoding Rules \\(DER\\)\"\")] format.",
            "Adjusted": "The CertificateAuthoritiesExtension structure contains a list of distinguished names of acceptable certificate authorities, represented in DER-encoded format as specified in X690."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These distinguished names specify a desired distinguished name for a trust anchor or subordinate CA; thus, this message can be used to describe known trust anchors as well as a desired authorization space.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY send the \"certificate_authorities\" extension in the ClientHello message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY send it in the CertificateRequest message.",
            "Adjusted": "The server MAY send the \"certificate_authorities\" extension in the CertificateRequest message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"trusted_ca_keys\" extension [RFC6066 Extensions: Extension Definitions\"\")], which serves a similar purpose but is more complicated, is not used in TLS 1.3 (although it may appear in ClientHello messages from clients which are offering prior versions of TLS).",
            "Adjusted": "The \"trusted_ca_keys\" extension, which serves a similar purpose but is more complicated, is not used in TLS 1.3, although it may appear in ClientHello messages from clients offering prior versions of TLS."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4.2.2. Cookie": [
        {
            "Original": "struct { opaque cookie<1..2^16-1>; } Cookie; Cookies serve two primary purposes: \\- Allowing the server to force the client to demonstrate reachability at their apparent network address (thus providing a measure of DoS protection).",
            "Adjusted": "Cookies serve two primary purposes: Allowing the server to force the client to demonstrate reachability at their apparent network address (thus providing a measure of DoS protection)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is primarily useful for non-connection-oriented transports (see [RFC6347] for an example of this).",
            "Adjusted": "This reachability demonstration is primarily useful for non-connection-oriented transports (see [RFC6347] for an example of this functionality)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Allowing the server to offload state to the client, thus allowing it to send a HelloRetryRequest without storing any state.",
            "Adjusted": "Allowing the server to offload state to the client, thus allowing the server to send a HelloRetryRequest without storing any state."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server can do this by storing the hash of the ClientHello in the HelloRetryRequest cookie (protected with some suitable integrity protection algorithm).",
            "Adjusted": "The server can offload state by storing the hash of the ClientHello in the HelloRetryRequest cookie (protected with some suitable integrity protection algorithm)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When sending a HelloRetryRequest, the server MAY provide a \"cookie\" extension to the client (this is an exception to the usual rule that the only extensions that may be sent are those that appear in the ClientHello).",
            "Adjusted": "When sending a HelloRetryRequest, the server MAY provide a \"cookie\" extension to the client (this cookie extension is an exception to the usual rule that the only extensions that may be sent are those that appear in the ClientHello)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When sending the new ClientHello, the client MUST copy the contents of the extension received in the HelloRetryRequest into a \"cookie\" extension in the new ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST NOT use cookies in their initial ClientHello in subsequent connections.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a server is operating statelessly, it may receive an unprotected record of type change_cipher_spec between the first and second ClientHello (see Section 5).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Since the server is not storing any state, this will appear as if it were the first message to be received.",
            "Adjusted": "Since the server is not storing any state, this change_cipher_spec record will appear as if it were the first message to be received."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers operating statelessly MUST ignore these records.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.1. Key Exchan:
{
    "4.1.1. Cryptographic Negotiation": [
        {
            "Original": "In TLS, the cryptographic negotiation proceeds by the client offering the following four sets of options in its ClientHello: \\- A list of cipher suites which indicates the AEAD algorithm/HKDF hash pairs which the client supports.",
            "Adjusted": "In TLS, the cryptographic negotiation proceeds by the client offering the following four sets of options in its ClientHello: A list of cipher suites which indicates the AEAD algorithm/HKDF hash pairs which the client supports."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- A \"supported_groups\" (Section 4.2.7) extension which indicates the (EC)DHE groups which the client supports and a \"key_share\" (Section 4.2.8) extension which contains (EC)DHE shares for some or all of these groups.",
            "Adjusted": "A \"supported_groups\" (Section 4.2.7) extension which indicates the (EC)DHE groups which the client supports and a \"key_share\" (Section 4.2.8) extension which contains (EC)DHE shares for some or all of these groups."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- A \"signature_algorithms\" (Section 4.2.3) extension which indicates the signature algorithms which the client can accept.",
            "Adjusted": "A \"signature_algorithms\" (Section 4.2.3) extension which indicates the signature algorithms which the client can accept."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A \"signature_algorithms_cert\" extension (Section 4.2.3) may also be added to indicate certificate-specific signature algorithms.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- A \"pre_shared_key\" (Section 4.2.11) extension which contains a list of symmetric key identities known to the client and a \"psk_key_exchange_modes\" (Section 4.2.9) extension which indicates the key exchange modes that may be used with PSKs.",
            "Adjusted": "A \"pre_shared_key\" (Section 4.2.11) extension which contains a list of symmetric key identities known to the client and a \"psk_key_exchange_modes\" (Section 4.2.9) extension which indicates the key exchange modes that may be used with PSKs."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server does not select a PSK, then the first three of these options are entirely orthogonal: the server independently selects a cipher suite, an (EC)DHE group and key share for key establishment, and a signature algorithm/certificate pair to authenticate itself to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If there is no overlap between the received \"supported_groups\" and the groups supported by the server, then the server MUST abort the handshake with a \"handshake_failure\" or an \"insufficient_security\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server selects a PSK, then it MUST also select a key establishment mode from the set indicated by the client's \"psk_key_exchange_modes\" extension (at present, PSK alone or with (EC)DHE).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that if the PSK can be used without (EC)DHE, then non-overlap in the \"supported_groups\" parameters need not be fatal, as it is in the non-PSK case discussed in the previous paragraph.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server selects an (EC)DHE group and the client did not offer a compatible \"key_share\" extension in the initial ClientHello, the server MUST respond with a HelloRetryRequest (Section 4.1.4) message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server successfully selects parameters and does not require a HelloRetryRequest, it indicates the selected parameters in the ServerHello as follows: \\- If PSK is being used, then the server will send a \"pre_shared_key\" extension indicating the selected key.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server successfully selects parameters and does not require a HelloRetryRequest, the server indicates the selected parameters in the ServerHello as follows: If PSK is being used, then the server will send a \"pre_shared_key\" extension indicating the selected key."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- When (EC)DHE is in use, the server will also provide a \"key_share\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "When (EC)DHE is in use, the server will also provide a \"key_share\" extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If PSK is not being used, then (EC)DHE and certificate-based authentication are always used.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- When authenticating via a certificate, the server will send the Certificate (Section 4.4.2) and CertificateVerify (Section 4.4.3) messages.",
            "Adjusted": "When authenticating via a certificate, the server will send the Certificate (Section 4.4.2) and CertificateVerify (Section 4.4.3) messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS 1.3 as defined by this document, either a PSK or a certificate is always used, but not both.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Future documents may define how to use them together.",
            "Adjusted": "Future documents may define how to use PSK and certificate together."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is unable to negotiate a supported set of parameters (i.e., there is no overlap between the client and server parameters), it MUST abort the handshake with either a \"handshake_failure\" or \"insufficient_security\" fatal alert (see Section 6).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Protocol Overview:
{
    "2. Protocol Overview": [
        {
            "Original": "The cryptographic parameters used by the secure channel are produced by the TLS handshake protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This sub-protocol of TLS is used by the client and server when first communicating with each other.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The handshake protocol allows peers to negotiate a protocol version, select cryptographic algorithms, optionally authenticate each other, and establish shared secret keying material.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once the handshake is complete, the peers use the established keys to protect the application-layer traffic.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A failure of the handshake or other protocol error triggers the termination of the connection, optionally preceded by an alert message (Section 6).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS supports three basic key exchange modes: \\- (EC)DHE (Diffie-Hellman over either finite fields or elliptic curves) \\- PSK-only \\- PSK with (EC)DHE Figure 1 below shows the basic full TLS handshake: Client Server Key ^ ClientHello Exch | + key_share* | + signature_algorithms* | + psk_key_exchange_modes* v + pre_shared_key* --------> ServerHello ^ Key \\+ key_share* | Exch \\+ pre_shared_key* v {EncryptedExtensions} ^ Server {CertificateRequest*} v Params {Certificate*} ^ {CertificateVerify*} | Auth {Finished} v <\\-------- [Application Data*] ^ {Certificate*} Auth | {CertificateVerify*} v {Finished} --------> [Application Data] <\\-------> [Application Data] \\+ Indicates noteworthy extensions sent in the previously noted message.",
            "Adjusted": "TLS supports three basic key exchange modes: (EC)DHE (Diffie-Hellman over either finite fields or elliptic curves), PSK-only, and PSK with (EC)DHE. Figure 1 below shows the basic full TLS handshake message flow between client and server. The handshake involves ClientHello, ServerHello, EncryptedExtensions, CertificateRequest, Certificate, CertificateVerify, and Finished messages, with optional extensions and application data exchange."
        },
        {
            "Original": "* Indicates optional or situation-dependent messages/extensions that are not always sent.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "{} Indicates messages protected using keys derived from a [sender]_handshake_traffic_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "Curly braces indicate messages protected using keys derived from a sender handshake traffic secret."
        },
        {
            "Original": "[] Indicates messages protected using keys derived from [sender]_application_traffic_secret_N.",
            "Adjusted": "Square brackets indicate messages protected using keys derived from sender application traffic secret N."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Figure 1: Message Flow for Full TLS Handshake The handshake can be thought of as having three phases (indicated in the diagram above): \\- Key Exchange: Establish shared keying material and select the cryptographic parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "The handshake can be thought of as having three phases: Key Exchange, which establishes shared keying material and selects the cryptographic parameters."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Everything after this phase is encrypted.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Server Parameters: Establish other handshake parameters (whether the client is authenticated, application-layer protocol support, etc.).",
            "Adjusted": "Server Parameters phase establishes other handshake parameters such as whether the client is authenticated and application-layer protocol support."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Authentication: Authenticate the server (and, optionally, the client) and provide key confirmation and handshake integrity.",
            "Adjusted": "Authentication phase authenticates the server and optionally the client, providing key confirmation and handshake integrity."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the Key Exchange phase, the client sends the ClientHello (Section 4.1.2) message, which contains a random nonce (ClientHello.random); its offered protocol versions; a list of symmetric cipher/HKDF hash pairs; either a set of Diffie-Hellman key shares (in the \"key_share\" (Section 4.2.8) extension), a set of pre-shared key labels (in the \"pre_shared_key\" (Section 4.2.11) extension), or both; and potentially additional extensions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additional fields and/or messages may also be present for middlebox compatibility.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server processes the ClientHello and determines the appropriate cryptographic parameters for the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It then responds with its own ServerHello (Section 4.1.3), which indicates the negotiated connection parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The combination of the ClientHello and the ServerHello determines the shared keys.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If (EC)DHE key establishment is in use, then the ServerHello contains a \"key_share\" extension with the server's ephemeral Diffie-Hellman share; the server's share MUST be in the same group as one of the client's shares.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If PSK key establishment is in use, then the ServerHello contains a \"pre_shared_key\" extension indicating which of the client's offered PSKs was selected.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that implementations can use (EC)DHE and PSK together, in which case both extensions will be supplied.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server then sends two messages to establish the Server Parameters: EncryptedExtensions: responses to ClientHello extensions that are not required to determine the cryptographic parameters, other than those that are specific to individual certificates.",
            "Adjusted": "The server then sends two messages to establish the Server Parameters: EncryptedExtensions provides responses to ClientHello extensions that are not required to determine cryptographic parameters, excluding those specific to individual certificates."
        },
        {
            "Original": "[Section 4.3.1] CertificateRequest: if certificate-based client authentication is desired, the desired parameters for that certificate.",
            "Adjusted": "CertificateRequest specifies desired parameters for certificate-based client authentication if it is desired."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message is omitted if client authentication is not desired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[Section 4.3.2] Finally, the client and server exchange Authentication messages.",
            "Adjusted": "Finally, the client and server exchange Authentication messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS uses the same set of messages every time that certificate-based authentication is needed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(PSK-based authentication happens as a side effect of key exchange.) Specifically: Certificate: The certificate of the endpoint and any per-certificate extensions.",
            "Adjusted": "PSK-based authentication happens as a side effect of key exchange. Specifically, Certificate message contains the certificate of the endpoint and any per-certificate extensions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message is omitted by the server if not authenticating with a certificate and by the client if the server did not send CertificateRequest (thus indicating that the client should not authenticate with a certificate).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that if raw public keys [RFC7250 and Datagram Transport Layer Security \\(DTLS\\)\"\")] or the cached information extension [RFC7924 Cached Information Extension\"\")] are in use, then this message will not contain a certificate but rather some other value corresponding to the server's long-term key.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that if raw public keys or the cached information extension are in use, then the Certificate message will not contain a certificate but rather some other value corresponding to the server's long-term key."
        },
        {
            "Original": "[Section 4.4.2] CertificateVerify: A signature over the entire handshake using the private key corresponding to the public key in the Certificate message.",
            "Adjusted": "CertificateVerify provides a signature over the entire handshake using the private key corresponding to the public key in the Certificate message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message is omitted if the endpoint is not authenticating via a certificate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[Section 4.4.3] Finished: A MAC (Message Authentication Code) over the entire handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "Finished provides a MAC (Message Authentication Code) over the entire handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message provides key confirmation, binds the endpoint's identity to the exchanged keys, and in PSK mode also authenticates the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[Section 4.4.4] Upon receiving the server's messages, the client responds with its Authentication messages, namely Certificate and CertificateVerify (if requested), and Finished.",
            "Adjusted": "Upon receiving the server's messages, the client responds with its Authentication messages, namely Certificate and CertificateVerify if requested, and Finished."
        },
        {
            "Original": "At this point, the handshake is complete, and the client and server derive the keying material required by the record layer to exchange application-layer data protected through authenticated encryption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application Data MUST NOT be sent prior to sending the Finished message, except as specified in Section 2.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that while the server may send Application Data prior to receiving the client's Authentication messages, any data sent at that point is, of course, being sent to an unauthenticated peer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4.2.5. OID Filters": [
        {
            "Original": "The \"oid_filters\" extension allows servers to provide a set of OID/value pairs which it would like the client's certificate to match.",
            "Adjusted": "The \"oid_filters\" extension allows servers to provide a set of OID/value pairs which the server would like the client's certificate to match."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This extension, if provided by the server, MUST only be sent in the CertificateRequest message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "struct { opaque certificate_extension_oid<1..2^8-1>; opaque certificate_extension_values<0..2^16-1>; } OIDFilter; struct { OIDFilter filters<0..2^16-1>; } OIDFilterExtension; filters: A list of certificate extension OIDs [RFC5280 Profile\"\")] with their allowed value(s) and represented in DER-encoded [X690, Canonical Encoding Rules \\(CER\\) and Distinguished Encoding Rules \\(DER\\)\"\")] format.",
            "Adjusted": "The OIDFilter structure contains certificate_extension_oid and certificate_extension_values fields. The OIDFilterExtension structure contains a filters list. The filters parameter is a list of certificate extension OIDs from RFC5280 Profile with their allowed values, represented in DER-encoded format as specified in X690 Canonical Encoding Rules and Distinguished Encoding Rules."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some certificate extension OIDs allow multiple values (e.g., Extended Key Usage).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server has included a non-empty filters list, the client certificate included in the response MUST contain all of the specified extension OIDs that the client recognizes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For each extension OID recognized by the client, all of the specified values MUST be present in the client certificate (but the certificate MAY have other values as well).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, the client MUST ignore and skip any unrecognized certificate extension OIDs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client ignored some of the required certificate extension OIDs and supplied a certificate that does not satisfy the request, the server MAY at its discretion either continue the connection without client authentication or abort the handshake with an \"unsupported_certificate\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any given OID MUST NOT appear more than once in the filters list.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "PKIX RFCs define a variety of certificate extension OIDs and their corresponding value types.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Depending on the type, matching certificate extension values are not necessarily bitwise-equal.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is expected that TLS implementations will rely on their PKI libraries to perform certificate selection using certificate extension OIDs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document defines matching rules for two standard certificate extensions defined in [RFC5280 Profile\"\")]: \\- The Key Usage extension in a certificate matches the request when all key usage bits asserted in the request are also asserted in the Key Usage certificate extension.",
            "Adjusted": "This document defines matching rules for two standard certificate extensions defined in RFC5280 Profile: The Key Usage extension in a certificate matches the request when all key usage bits asserted in the request are also asserted in the Key Usage certificate extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The Extended Key Usage extension in a certificate matches the request when all key purpose OIDs present in the request are also found in the Extended Key Usage certificate extension.",
            "Adjusted": "The Extended Key Usage extension in a certificate matches the request when all key purpose OIDs present in the request are also found in the Extended Key Usage certificate extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The special anyExtendedKeyUsage OID MUST NOT be used in the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Separate specifications may define matching rules for other certificate extensions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.8. Key Share -> 4.2.8.1. Diffie-Hellman Parameters": [
        {
            "Original": "Diffie-Hellman [DH76] parameters for both clients and servers are encoded in the opaque key_exchange field of a KeyShareEntry in a KeyShare structure.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The opaque value contains the Diffie-Hellman public value (Y = g^X mod p) for the specified group (see [RFC7919\"\")] for group definitions) encoded as a big-endian integer and padded to the left with zeros to the size of p in bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "The opaque value contains the Diffie-Hellman public value (Y = g^X mod p) for the specified group (see RFC7919 for group definitions) encoded as a big-endian integer and padded to the left with zeros to the size of p in bytes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: For a given Diffie-Hellman group, the padding results in all public keys having the same length.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Peers MUST validate each other's public key Y by ensuring that 1 < Y < p-1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This check ensures that the remote peer is properly behaved and isn't forcing the local system into a small subgroup.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.1. Key Exchan:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.1. Key Exchange Messages -> 4.1.4. Hello Retry Request": [
        {
            "Original": "The server will send this message in response to a ClientHello message if it is able to find an acceptable set of parameters but the ClientHello does not contain sufficient information to proceed with the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "The server will send the HelloRetryRequest message in response to a ClientHello message if the server is able to find an acceptable set of parameters but the ClientHello does not contain sufficient information to proceed with the handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "As discussed inSection 4.1.3, the HelloRetryRequest has the same format as a ServerHello message, and the legacy_version, legacy_session_id_echo, cipher_suite, and legacy_compression_method fields have the same meaning.",
            "Adjusted": "As discussed in Section 4.1.3, the HelloRetryRequest has the same format as a ServerHello message, and the legacy_version, legacy_session_id_echo, cipher_suite, and legacy_compression_method fields have the same meaning."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, for convenience we discuss \"HelloRetryRequest\" throughout this document as if it were a distinct message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server's extensions MUST contain \"supported_versions\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additionally, it SHOULD contain the minimal set of extensions necessary for the client to generate a correct ClientHello pair.",
            "Adjusted": "Additionally, the HelloRetryRequest SHOULD contain the minimal set of extensions necessary for the client to generate a correct ClientHello pair."
        },
        {
            "Original": "As with the ServerHello, a HelloRetryRequest MUST NOT contain any extensions that were not first offered by the client in its ClientHello, with the exception of optionally the \"cookie\" (see Section 4.2.2) extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of a HelloRetryRequest, the client MUST check the legacy_version, legacy_session_id_echo, cipher_suite, and legacy_compression_method as specified in Section 4.1.3 and then process the extensions, starting with determining the version using \"supported_versions\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert if the HelloRetryRequest would not result in any change in the ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a client receives a second HelloRetryRequest in the same connection (i.e., where the ClientHello was itself in response to a HelloRetryRequest), it MUST abort the handshake with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "If a client receives a second HelloRetryRequest in the same connection (i.e., where the ClientHello was itself in response to a HelloRetryRequest), the client MUST abort the handshake with an \"unexpected_message\" alert."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise, the client MUST process all extensions in the HelloRetryRequest and send a second updated ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The HelloRetryRequest extensions defined in this specification are: \\- supported_versions (see Section 4.2.1) \\- cookie (see Section 4.2.2) \\- key_share (see Section 4.2.8) A client which receives a cipher suite that was not offered MUST abort the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "The HelloRetryRequest extensions defined in this specification are: supported_versions (see Section 4.2.1), cookie (see Section 4.2.2), and key_share (see Section 4.2.8). A client which receives a cipher suite that was not offered MUST abort the handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST ensure that they negotiate the same cipher suite when receiving a conformant updated ClientHello (if the server selects the cipher suite as the first step in the negotiation, then this will happen automatically).",
            "Adjusted": "Servers MUST ensure that they negotiate the same cipher suite when receiving a conformant updated ClientHello (if the server selects the cipher suite as the first step in the negotiation, then the same cipher suite negotiation will happen automatically)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receiving the ServerHello, clients MUST check that the cipher suite supplied in the ServerHello is the same as that in the HelloRetryRequest and otherwise abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, in its updated ClientHello, the client SHOULD NOT offer any pre-shared keys associated with a hash other than that of the selected cipher suite.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This allows the client to avoid having to compute partial hash transcripts for multiple hashes in the second ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "This restriction allows the client to avoid having to compute partial hash transcripts for multiple hashes in the second ClientHello."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of selected_version in the HelloRetryRequest \"supported_versions\" extension MUST be retained in the ServerHello, and a client MUST abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert if the value changes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4.2.1. Supported Versions": [
        {
            "Original": "struct { select (Handshake.msg_type) { case client_hello: ProtocolVersion versions<2..254>; case server_hello: /* and HelloRetryRequest */ ProtocolVersion selected_version; }; } SupportedVersions; The \"supported_versions\" extension is used by the client to indicate which versions of TLS it supports and by the server to indicate which version it is using.",
            "Adjusted": "The SupportedVersions structure is defined as: for client_hello, it contains a list of ProtocolVersion values; for server_hello, it contains a single ProtocolVersion value. The \"supported_versions\" extension is used by the client to indicate which versions of TLS the client supports and by the server to indicate which version the server is using."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The extension contains a list of supported versions in preference order, with the most preferred version first.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations of this specification MUST send this extension in the ClientHello containing all versions of TLS which they are prepared to negotiate (for this specification, that means minimally 0x0304, but if previous versions of TLS are allowed to be negotiated, they MUST be present as well).",
            "Adjusted": "Implementations of this specification MUST send this extension in the ClientHello containing all versions of TLS which the implementations are prepared to negotiate (for this specification, that means minimally 0x0304, but if previous versions of TLS are allowed to be negotiated, the previous versions MUST be present as well)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this extension is not present, servers which are compliant with this specification and which also support TLS 1.2 MUST negotiate TLS 1.2 or prior as specified in [RFC5246 Protocol Version 1.2\"\"]), even if ClientHello.legacy_version is 0x0304 or later.",
            "Adjusted": "If this extension is not present, servers which are compliant with this specification and which also support TLS 1.2 MUST negotiate TLS 1.2 or prior as specified in RFC5246, even if ClientHello.legacy_version is 0x0304 or later."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MAY abort the handshake upon receiving a ClientHello with legacy_version 0x0304 or later.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this extension is present in the ClientHello, servers MUST NOT use the ClientHello.legacy_version value for version negotiation and MUST use only the \"supported_versions\" extension to determine client preferences.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST only select a version of TLS present in that extension and MUST ignore any unknown versions that are present in that extension.",
            "Adjusted": "Servers MUST only select a version of TLS present in the \"supported_versions\" extension and MUST ignore any unknown versions that are present in the extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that this mechanism makes it possible to negotiate a version prior to TLS 1.2 if one side supports a sparse range.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations of TLS 1.3 which choose to support prior versions of TLS SHOULD support TLS 1.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST be prepared to receive ClientHellos that include this extension but do not include 0x0304 in the list of versions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server which negotiates a version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 MUST set ServerHello.version and MUST NOT send the \"supported_versions\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server which negotiates TLS 1.3 MUST respond by sending a \"supported_versions\" extension containing the selected version value (0x0304).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It MUST set the ServerHello.legacy_version field to 0x0303 (TLS 1.2).",
            "Adjusted": "The server MUST set the ServerHello.legacy_version field to 0x0303 (TLS 1.2)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST check for this extension prior to processing the rest of the ServerHello (although they will have to parse the ServerHello in order to read the extension).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this extension is present, clients MUST ignore the ServerHello.legacy_version value and MUST use only the \"supported_versions\" extension to determine the selected version.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the \"supported_versions\" extension in the ServerHello contains a version not offered by the client or contains a version prior to TLS 1.3, the client MUST abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.7. Supported Groups": [
        {
            "Original": "When sent by the client, the \"supported_groups\" extension indicates the named groups which the client supports for key exchange, ordered from most preferred to least preferred.",
