4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.11. Pre-Shared Key Extension": [
        {
            "Original": "The \"pre_shared_key\" extension is used to negotiate the identity of the pre-shared key to be used with a given handshake in association with PSK key establishment.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"extension_data\" field of this extension contains a \"PreSharedKeyExtension\" value: struct { opaque identity<1..2^16-1>; uint32 obfuscated_ticket_age; } PskIdentity; opaque PskBinderEntry<32..255>; struct { PskIdentity identities<7..2^16-1>; PskBinderEntry binders<33..2^16-1>; } OfferedPsks; struct { select (Handshake.msg_type) { case client_hello: OfferedPsks; case server_hello: uint16 selected_identity; }; } PreSharedKeyExtension; identity: A label for a key.",
            "Adjusted": "The \"extension_data\" field of the \"pre_shared_key\" extension contains a \"PreSharedKeyExtension\" value. The structure includes: PskIdentity with identity (a label for a key) and obfuscated_ticket_age; PskBinderEntry; OfferedPsks with identities and binders; and PreSharedKeyExtension which varies by handshake message type."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For instance, a ticket (as defined in Appendix B.3.4) or a label for a pre-shared key established externally.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "obfuscated_ticket_age: An obfuscated version of the age of the key.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 4.2.11.1 describes how to form this value for identities established via the NewSessionTicket message.",
            "Adjusted": "Section 4.2.11.1 describes how to form the obfuscated_ticket_age value for identities established via the NewSessionTicket message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For identities established externally, an obfuscated_ticket_age of 0 SHOULD be used, and servers MUST ignore the value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "identities: A list of the identities that the client is willing to negotiate with the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If sent alongside the \"early_data\" extension (see Section 4.2.10), the first identity is the one used for 0-RTT data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "binders: A series of HMAC values, one for each value in the identities list and in the same order, computed as described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "selected_identity: The server's chosen identity expressed as a (0-based) index into the identities in the client's list.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each PSK is associated with a single Hash algorithm.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For PSKs established via the ticket mechanism (Section 4.6.1), this is the KDF Hash algorithm on the connection where the ticket was established.",
            "Adjusted": "For PSKs established via the ticket mechanism (Section 4.6.1), the Hash algorithm is the KDF Hash algorithm on the connection where the ticket was established."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For externally established PSKs, the Hash algorithm MUST be set when the PSK is established or default to SHA-256 if no such algorithm is defined.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST ensure that it selects a compatible PSK (if any) and cipher suite.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS versions prior to TLS 1.3, the Server Name Identification (SNI) value was intended to be associated with the session ([Section 3 of [RFC6066]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6066#section-3)), with the server being required to enforce that the SNI value associated with the session matches the one specified in the resumption handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "In TLS versions prior to TLS 1.3, the Server Name Identification (SNI) value was intended to be associated with the session (Section 3 of RFC6066), with the server being required to enforce that the SNI value associated with the session matches the one specified in the resumption handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, in reality the implementations were not consistent on which of two supplied SNI values they would use, leading to the consistency requirement being de facto enforced by the clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS 1.3, the SNI value is always explicitly specified in the resumption handshake, and there is no need for the server to associate an SNI value with the ticket.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients, however, SHOULD store the SNI with the PSK to fulfill the requirements of Section 4.6.1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementor's note: When session resumption is the primary use case of PSKs, the most straightforward way to implement the PSK/cipher suite matching requirements is to negotiate the cipher suite first and then exclude any incompatible PSKs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any unknown PSKs (e.g., ones not in the PSK database or encrypted with an unknown key) SHOULD simply be ignored.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If no acceptable PSKs are found, the server SHOULD perform a non-PSK handshake if possible.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If backward compatibility is important, client-provided, externally established PSKs SHOULD influence cipher suite selection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Prior to accepting PSK key establishment, the server MUST validate the corresponding binder value (see Section 4.2.11.2 below).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this value is not present or does not validate, the server MUST abort the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "If the binder value is not present or does not validate, the server MUST abort the handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers SHOULD NOT attempt to validate multiple binders; rather, they SHOULD select a single PSK and validate solely the binder that corresponds to that PSK.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Section 8.2 and Appendix E.6 for the security rationale for this requirement.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to accept PSK key establishment, the server sends a \"pre_shared_key\" extension indicating the selected identity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST verify that the server's selected_identity is within the range supplied by the client, that the server selected a cipher suite indicating a Hash associated with the PSK, and that a server \"key_share\" extension is present if required by the ClientHello \"psk_key_exchange_modes\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If these values are not consistent, the client MUST abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server supplies an \"early_data\" extension, the client MUST verify that the server's selected_identity is 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If any other value is returned, the client MUST abort the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"pre_shared_key\" extension MUST be the last extension in the ClientHello (this facilitates implementation as described below).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST check that it is the last extension and otherwise fail the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "Servers MUST check that the \"pre_shared_key\" extension is the last extension and otherwise fail the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert."
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.4. Authentica:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.4. Authentication Messages -> 4.4.2. Certificate -> 4.4.2.4. Receiving a Certificate Message": [
        {
            "Original": "In general, detailed certificate validation procedures are out of scope for TLS (see [RFC5280 Profile\"\")]).",
            "Adjusted": "In general, detailed certificate validation procedures are out of scope for TLS (see RFC5280 Profile)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This section provides TLS-specific requirements.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server supplies an empty Certificate message, the client MUST abort the handshake with a \"decode_error\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client does not send any certificates (i.e., it sends an empty Certificate message), the server MAY at its discretion either continue the handshake without client authentication or abort the handshake with a \"certificate_required\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, if some aspect of the certificate chain was unacceptable (e.g., it was not signed by a known, trusted CA), the server MAY at its discretion either continue the handshake (considering the client unauthenticated) or abort the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any endpoint receiving any certificate which it would need to validate using any signature algorithm using an MD5 hash MUST abort the handshake with a \"bad_certificate\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "SHA-1 is deprecated, and it is RECOMMENDED that any endpoint receiving any certificate which it would need to validate using any signature algorithm using a SHA-1 hash abort the handshake with a \"bad_certificate\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For clarity, this means that endpoints can accept these algorithms for certificates that are self-signed or are trust anchors.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "All endpoints are RECOMMENDED to transition to SHA-256 or better as soon as possible to maintain interoperability with implementations currently in the process of phasing out SHA-1 support.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that a certificate containing a key for one signature algorithm MAY be signed using a different signature algorithm (for instance, an RSA key signed with an ECDSA key).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.5. End of Ear:
{
    "4.5. End of Early Data": [
        {
            "Original": "struct {} EndOfEarlyData; If the server sent an \"early_data\" extension in EncryptedExtensions, the client MUST send an EndOfEarlyData message after receiving the server Finished.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server sent an \"early_data\" extension in EncryptedExtensions, the client MUST send an EndOfEarlyData message after receiving the server Finished."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server does not send an \"early_data\" extension in EncryptedExtensions, then the client MUST NOT send an EndOfEarlyData message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message indicates that all 0-RTT application_data messages, if any, have been transmitted and that the following records are protected under handshake traffic keys.",
            "Adjusted": "The EndOfEarlyData message indicates that all 0-RTT application_data messages, if any, have been transmitted and that the following records are protected under handshake traffic keys."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST NOT send this message, and clients receiving it MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "Servers MUST NOT send the EndOfEarlyData message, and clients receiving the EndOfEarlyData message MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message is encrypted under keys derived from the client_early_traffic_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "The EndOfEarlyData message is encrypted under keys derived from the client_early_traffic_secret."
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.4. Authentica:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.4. Authentication Messages -> 4.4.2. Certificate -> 4.4.2.2. Server Certificate Selection": [
        {
            "Original": "The following rules apply to the certificates sent by the server: \\- The certificate type MUST be X.509v3 [RFC5280 Profile\"\")], unless explicitly negotiated otherwise (e.g., [RFC7250 and Datagram Transport Layer Security \\(DTLS\\)\"\")]).",
            "Adjusted": "The following rules apply to the certificates sent by the server: The certificate type MUST be X.509v3 as specified in RFC5280 Profile, unless explicitly negotiated otherwise, such as with RFC7250 and Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The server's end-entity certificate's public key (and associated restrictions) MUST be compatible with the selected authentication algorithm from the client's \"signature_algorithms\" extension (currently RSA, ECDSA, or EdDSA).",
            "Adjusted": "The server's end-entity certificate's public key and associated restrictions MUST be compatible with the selected authentication algorithm from the client's signature_algorithms extension, which currently includes RSA, ECDSA, or EdDSA."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The certificate MUST allow the key to be used for signing (i.e., the digitalSignature bit MUST be set if the Key Usage extension is present) with a signature scheme indicated in the client's \"signature_algorithms\"/\"signature_algorithms_cert\" extensions (see Section 4.2.3).",
            "Adjusted": "The certificate MUST allow the key to be used for signing, meaning the digitalSignature bit MUST be set if the Key Usage extension is present, with a signature scheme indicated in the client's signature_algorithms or signature_algorithms_cert extensions as described in Section 4.2.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The \"server_name\" [RFC6066 Extensions: Extension Definitions\"\")] and \"certificate_authorities\" extensions are used to guide certificate selection.",
            "Adjusted": "The server_name extension as defined in RFC6066 and the certificate_authorities extension are used to guide certificate selection."
        },
        {
            "Original": "As servers MAY require the presence of the \"server_name\" extension, clients SHOULD send this extension, when applicable.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "All certificates provided by the server MUST be signed by a signature algorithm advertised by the client if it is able to provide such a chain (see Section 4.2.3).",
            "Adjusted": "All certificates provided by the server MUST be signed by a signature algorithm advertised by the client if the server is able to provide such a chain, as described in Section 4.2.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Certificates that are self-signed or certificates that are expected to be trust anchors are not validated as part of the chain and therefore MAY be signed with any algorithm.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server cannot produce a certificate chain that is signed only via the indicated supported algorithms, then it SHOULD continue the handshake by sending the client a certificate chain of its choice that may include algorithms that are not known to be supported by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server cannot produce a certificate chain that is signed only via the indicated supported algorithms, then the server SHOULD continue the handshake by sending the client a certificate chain of its choice that may include algorithms not known to be supported by the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This fallback chain SHOULD NOT use the deprecated SHA-1 hash algorithm in general, but MAY do so if the client's advertisement permits it, and MUST NOT do so otherwise.",
            "Adjusted": "This fallback chain SHOULD NOT use the deprecated SHA-1 hash algorithm in general, but MAY use SHA-1 if the client's advertisement permits it, and MUST NOT use SHA-1 otherwise."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client cannot construct an acceptable chain using the provided certificates and decides to abort the handshake, then it MUST abort the handshake with an appropriate certificate-related alert (by default, \"unsupported_certificate\"; see Section 6.2 for more information).",
            "Adjusted": "If the client cannot construct an acceptable chain using the provided certificates and decides to abort the handshake, then the client MUST abort the handshake with an appropriate certificate-related alert, such as unsupported_certificate by default, as detailed in Section 6.2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server has multiple certificates, it chooses one of them based on the above-mentioned criteria (in addition to other criteria, such as transport-layer endpoint, local configuration, and preferences).",
            "Adjusted": "If the server has multiple certificates, the server chooses one of them based on the above-mentioned criteria, in addition to other criteria such as transport-layer endpoint, local configuration, and preferences."
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.10. Early Data Indication": [
        {
            "Original": "When a PSK is used and early data is allowed for that PSK, the client can send Application Data in its first flight of messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client opts to do so, it MUST supply both the \"pre_shared_key\" and \"early_data\" extensions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"extension_data\" field of this extension contains an \"EarlyDataIndication\" value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "struct {} Empty; struct { select (Handshake.msg_type) { case new_session_ticket: uint32 max_early_data_size; case client_hello: Empty; case encrypted_extensions: Empty; }; } EarlyDataIndication; See Section 4.6.1 for details regarding the use of the max_early_data_size field.",
            "Adjusted": "The EarlyDataIndication structure is defined with different cases for handshake message types: for new_session_ticket it contains a max_early_data_size field, while for client_hello and encrypted_extensions it contains an empty structure. See Section 4.6.1 for details regarding the use of the max_early_data_size field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The parameters for the 0-RTT data (version, symmetric cipher suite, Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) [RFC7301 Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation Extension\"\")] protocol, etc.) are those associated with the PSK in use.",
            "Adjusted": "The parameters for the 0-RTT data (version, symmetric cipher suite, Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) protocol, etc.) are those associated with the PSK in use."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For externally provisioned PSKs, the associated values are those provisioned along with the key.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For PSKs established via a NewSessionTicket message, the associated values are those which were negotiated in the connection which established the PSK.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The PSK used to encrypt the early data MUST be the first PSK listed in the client's \"pre_shared_key\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For PSKs provisioned via NewSessionTicket, a server MUST validate that the ticket age for the selected PSK identity (computed by subtracting ticket_age_add from PskIdentity.obfuscated_ticket_age modulo 2^32) is within a small tolerance of the time since the ticket was issued (see Section 8).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If it is not, the server SHOULD proceed with the handshake but reject 0-RTT, and SHOULD NOT take any other action that assumes that this ClientHello is fresh.",
            "Adjusted": "If the ticket age is not within tolerance, the server SHOULD proceed with the handshake but reject 0-RTT, and SHOULD NOT take any other action that assumes that this ClientHello is fresh."
        },
        {
            "Original": "0-RTT messages sent in the first flight have the same (encrypted) content types as messages of the same type sent in other flights (handshake and application_data) but are protected under different keys.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "After receiving the server's Finished message, if the server has accepted early data, an EndOfEarlyData message will be sent to indicate the key change.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message will be encrypted with the 0-RTT traffic keys.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server which receives an \"early_data\" extension MUST behave in one of three ways: \\- Ignore the extension and return a regular 1-RTT response.",
            "Adjusted": "A server which receives an \"early_data\" extension MUST behave in one of three ways: Ignore the extension and return a regular 1-RTT response."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server then skips past early data by attempting to deprotect received records using the handshake traffic key, discarding records which fail deprotection (up to the configured max_early_data_size).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once a record is deprotected successfully, it is treated as the start of the client's second flight and the server proceeds as with an ordinary 1-RTT handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Request that the client send another ClientHello by responding with a HelloRetryRequest.",
            "Adjusted": "Request that the client send another ClientHello by responding with a HelloRetryRequest."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client MUST NOT include the \"early_data\" extension in its followup ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server then ignores early data by skipping all records with an external content type of \"application_data\" (indicating that they are encrypted), up to the configured max_early_data_size.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Return its own \"early_data\" extension in EncryptedExtensions, indicating that it intends to process the early data.",
            "Adjusted": "Return its own \"early_data\" extension in EncryptedExtensions, indicating that it intends to process the early data."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is not possible for the server to accept only a subset of the early data messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Even though the server sends a message accepting early data, the actual early data itself may already be in flight by the time the server generates this message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to accept early data, the server MUST have accepted a PSK cipher suite and selected the first key offered in the client's \"pre_shared_key\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, it MUST verify that the following values are the same as those associated with the selected PSK: \\- The TLS version number \\- The selected cipher suite \\- The selected ALPN [RFC7301 Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation Extension\"\")] protocol, if any These requirements are a superset of those needed to perform a 1-RTT handshake using the PSK in question.",
            "Adjusted": "In addition, the server MUST verify that the following values are the same as those associated with the selected PSK: The TLS version number, the selected cipher suite, and the selected ALPN protocol if any. These requirements are a superset of those needed to perform a 1-RTT handshake using the PSK in question."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For externally established PSKs, the associated values are those provisioned along with the key.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For PSKs established via a NewSessionTicket message, the associated values are those negotiated in the connection during which the ticket was established.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Future extensions MUST define their interaction with 0-RTT.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If any of these checks fail, the server MUST NOT respond with the extension and must discard all the first-flight data using one of the first two mechanisms listed above (thus falling back to 1-RTT or 2-RTT).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client attempts a 0-RTT handshake but the server rejects it, the server will generally not have the 0-RTT record protection keys and must instead use trial decryption (either with the 1-RTT handshake keys or by looking for a cleartext ClientHello in the case of a HelloRetryRequest) to find the first non-0-RTT message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server chooses to accept the \"early_data\" extension, then it MUST comply with the same error-handling requirements specified for all records when processing early data records.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specifically, if the server fails to decrypt a 0-RTT record following an accepted \"early_data\" extension, it MUST terminate the connection with a \"bad_record_mac\" alert as per Section 5.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server rejects the \"early_data\" extension, the client application MAY opt to retransmit the Application Data previously sent in early data once the handshake has been completed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that automatic retransmission of early data could result in incorrect assumptions regarding the status of the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For instance, when the negotiated connection selects a different ALPN protocol from what was used for the early data, an application might need to construct different messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Similarly, if early data assumes anything about the connection state, it might be sent in error after the handshake completes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A TLS implementation SHOULD NOT automatically resend early data; applications are in a better position to decide when retransmission is appropriate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A TLS implementation MUST NOT automatically resend early data unless the negotiated connection selects the same ALPN protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.6. Post-Hands:
{
    "4.6.2. Post-Handshake Authentication": [
        {
            "Original": "When the client has sent the \"post_handshake_auth\" extension (seeSection 4.2.6), a server MAY request client authentication at any time after the handshake has completed by sending a CertificateRequest message.",
            "Adjusted": "When the client has sent the \"post_handshake_auth\" extension (see Section 4.2.6), a server MAY request client authentication at any time after the handshake has completed by sending a CertificateRequest message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST respond with the appropriate Authentication messages (see Section 4.4).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client chooses to authenticate, it MUST send Certificate, CertificateVerify, and Finished.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client chooses to authenticate, the client MUST send Certificate, CertificateVerify, and Finished messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If it declines, it MUST send a Certificate message containing no certificates followed by Finished.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client declines, the client MUST send a Certificate message containing no certificates followed by a Finished message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "All of the client's messages for a given response MUST appear consecutively on the wire with no intervening messages of other types.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client that receives a CertificateRequest message without having sent the \"post_handshake_auth\" extension MUST send an \"unexpected_message\" fatal alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: Because client authentication could involve prompting the user, servers MUST be prepared for some delay, including receiving an arbitrary number of other messages between sending the CertificateRequest and receiving a response.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, clients which receive multiple CertificateRequests in close succession MAY respond to them in a different order than they were received (the certificate_request_context value allows the server to disambiguate the responses).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.4. Authentica:
{
    "4.4.2. Certificate": [
        {
            "Original": "This message conveys the endpoint's certificate chain to the peer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST send a Certificate message whenever the agreed-upon key exchange method uses certificates for authentication (this includes all key exchange methods defined in this document except PSK).",
            "Adjusted": "The server MUST send a Certificate message whenever the agreed-upon key exchange method uses certificates for authentication (this includes all key exchange methods defined in this document except PSK)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST send a Certificate message if and only if the server has requested client authentication via a CertificateRequest message (Section 4.3.2).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server requests client authentication but no suitable certificate is available, the client MUST send a Certificate message containing no certificates (i.e., with the \"certificate_list\" field having length 0).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A Finished message MUST be sent regardless of whether the Certificate message is empty.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Structure of this message: enum { X509(0), RawPublicKey(2), (255) } CertificateType; struct { select (certificate_type) { case RawPublicKey: /* From RFC 7250 ASN.1_subjectPublicKeyInfo */ opaque ASN1_subjectPublicKeyInfo<1..2^24-1>; case X509: opaque cert_data<1..2^24-1>; }; Extension extensions<0..2^16-1>; } CertificateEntry; struct { opaque certificate_request_context<0..2^8-1>; CertificateEntry certificate_list<0..2^24-1>; } Certificate; certificate_request_context: If this message is in response to a CertificateRequest, the value of certificate_request_context in that message.",
            "Adjusted": "The structure of the Certificate message includes: an enumeration of certificate types (X509(0), RawPublicKey(2), and others up to 255); a CertificateEntry structure that contains either an ASN.1 subjectPublicKeyInfo for RawPublicKey or certificate data for X509, along with extensions; and a Certificate structure with certificate_request_context and certificate_list fields. The certificate_request_context field contains the value from the CertificateRequest message if this message is a response to one."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise (in the case of server authentication), this field SHALL be zero length.",
            "Adjusted": "Otherwise, in the case of server authentication, the certificate_request_context field SHALL be zero length."
        },
        {
            "Original": "certificate_list: A sequence (chain) of CertificateEntry structures, each containing a single certificate and set of extensions.",
            "Adjusted": "The certificate_list is a sequence (chain) of CertificateEntry structures, each containing a single certificate and set of extensions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "extensions: A set of extension values for the CertificateEntry.",
            "Adjusted": "The extensions are a set of extension values for the CertificateEntry."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"Extension\" format is defined in Section 4.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Valid extensions for server certificates at present include the OCSP Status extension [RFC6066 Extensions: Extension Definitions\"\")] and the SignedCertificateTimestamp extension [RFC6962]; future extensions may be defined for this message as well.",
            "Adjusted": "Valid extensions for server certificates at present include the OCSP Status extension from RFC6066 and the SignedCertificateTimestamp extension from RFC6962; future extensions may be defined for this message as well."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Extensions in the Certificate message from the server MUST correspond to ones from the ClientHello message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Extensions in the Certificate message from the client MUST correspond to extensions in the CertificateRequest message from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If an extension applies to the entire chain, it SHOULD be included in the first CertificateEntry.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the corresponding certificate type extension (\"server_certificate_type\" or \"client_certificate_type\") was not negotiated in EncryptedExtensions, or the X.509 certificate type was negotiated, then each CertificateEntry contains a DER-encoded X.509 certificate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The sender's certificate MUST come in the first CertificateEntry in the list.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each following certificate SHOULD directly certify the one immediately preceding it.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because certificate validation requires that trust anchors be distributed independently, a certificate that specifies a trust anchor MAY be omitted from the chain, provided that supported peers are known to possess any omitted certificates.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: Prior to TLS 1.3, \"certificate_list\" ordering required each certificate to certify the one immediately preceding it; however, some implementations allowed some flexibility.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers sometimes send both a current and deprecated intermediate for transitional purposes, and others are simply configured incorrectly, but these cases can nonetheless be validated properly.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For maximum compatibility, all implementations SHOULD be prepared to handle potentially extraneous certificates and arbitrary orderings from any TLS version, with the exception of the end-entity certificate which MUST be first.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the RawPublicKey certificate type was negotiated, then the certificate_list MUST contain no more than one CertificateEntry, which contains an ASN1_subjectPublicKeyInfo value as defined in [[RFC7250], Section 3](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7250#section-3).",
            "Adjusted": "If the RawPublicKey certificate type was negotiated, then the certificate_list MUST contain no more than one CertificateEntry, which contains an ASN.1 subjectPublicKeyInfo value as defined in RFC7250, Section 3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The OpenPGP certificate type [RFC6091 Authentication\"\")] MUST NOT be used with TLS 1.3.",
            "Adjusted": "The OpenPGP certificate type from RFC6091 MUST NOT be used with TLS 1.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server's certificate_list MUST always be non-empty.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client will send an empty certificate_list if it does not have an appropriate certificate to send in response to the server's authentication request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions:
{
    "4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.2. Extensions -> 4.2.3. Signature Algorithms": [
        {
            "Original": "TLS 1.3 provides two extensions for indicating which signature algorithms may be used in digital signatures.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"signature_algorithms_cert\" extension applies to signatures in certificates, and the \"signature_algorithms\" extension, which originally appeared in TLS 1.2, applies to signatures in CertificateVerify messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The keys found in certificates MUST also be of appropriate type for the signature algorithms they are used with.",
            "Adjusted": "The keys found in certificates MUST also be of appropriate type for the signature algorithms the keys are used with."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is a particular issue for RSA keys and PSS signatures, as described below.",
            "Adjusted": "The requirement for keys to be of appropriate type for signature algorithms is a particular issue for RSA keys and PSS signatures, as described below."
