5. Record Protocol -> 5.4. Record Paddin:
{
    "5. Record Protocol -> 5.4. Record Padding": [
        {
            "Original": "All encrypted TLS records can be padded to inflate the size of the TLSCiphertext.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This allows the sender to hide the size of the traffic from an observer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When generating a TLSCiphertext record, implementations MAY choose to pad.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An unpadded record is just a record with a padding length of zero.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Padding is a string of zero-valued bytes appended to the ContentType field before encryption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST set the padding octets to all zeros before encrypting.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application Data records may contain a zero-length TLSInnerPlaintext.content if the sender desires.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This permits generation of plausibly sized cover traffic in contexts where the presence or absence of activity may be sensitive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST NOT send Handshake and Alert records that have a zero-length TLSInnerPlaintext.content; if such a message is received, the receiving implementation MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The padding sent is automatically verified by the record protection mechanism; upon successful decryption of a TLSCiphertext.encrypted_record, the receiving implementation scans the field from the end toward the beginning until it finds a non-zero octet.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This non-zero octet is the content type of the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This padding scheme was selected because it allows padding of any encrypted TLS record by an arbitrary size (from zero up to TLS record size limits) without introducing new content types.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The design also enforces all-zero padding octets, which allows for quick detection of padding errors.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST limit their scanning to the cleartext returned from the AEAD decryption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a receiving implementation does not find a non-zero octet in the cleartext, it MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The presence of padding does not change the overall record size limitations: the full encoded TLSInnerPlaintext MUST NOT exceed 2^14 \\+ 1 octets.",
            "Adjusted": "The presence of padding does not change the overall record size limitations: the full encoded TLSInnerPlaintext MUST NOT exceed 2^14 + 1 octets."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the maximum fragment length is reduced -- as, for example, by the record_size_limit extension from [RFC8449] -- then the reduced limit applies to the full plaintext, including the content type and padding.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Selecting a padding policy that suggests when and how much to pad is a complex topic and is beyond the scope of this specification.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the application-layer protocol on top of TLS has its own padding, it may be preferable to pad Application Data TLS records within the application layer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Padding for encrypted Handshake or Alert records must still be handled at the TLS layer, though.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Later documents may define padding selection algorithms or define a padding policy request mechanism through TLS extensions or some other means.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.2. Up:
{
    "7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.2. Updating Traffic Secrets": [
        {
            "Original": "Once the handshake is complete, it is possible for either side to update its sending traffic keys using the KeyUpdate handshake message defined inSection 4.6.3.",
            "Adjusted": "Once the handshake is complete, it is possible for either side to update its sending traffic keys using the KeyUpdate handshake message defined in Section 4.6.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The next generation of traffic keys is computed by generating client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N+1 from client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N as described in this section and then re-deriving the traffic keys as described in Section 7.3.",
            "Adjusted": "The next generation of traffic keys is computed by generating client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N+1 from client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N as described in this section and then re-deriving the traffic keys as described in Section 7.3."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The next-generation application_traffic_secret is computed as: application_traffic_secret_N+1 = HKDF-Expand-Label(application_traffic_secret_N, \"traffic upd\", \"\", Hash.length) Once client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N+1 and its associated traffic keys have been computed, implementations SHOULD delete client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N and its associated traffic keys.",
            "Adjusted": "The next-generation application_traffic_secret is computed as: application_traffic_secret_N+1 = HKDF-Expand-Label(application_traffic_secret_N, \"traffic upd\", \"\", Hash.length). Once client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N+1 and its associated traffic keys have been computed, implementations SHOULD delete client_/server_application_traffic_secret_N and its associated traffic keys."
        }
