7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.3. Tr:
{
    "7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.3. Traffic Key Calculation": [
        {
            "Original": "The traffic keying material is generated from the following input values: \\- A secret value \\- A purpose value indicating the specific value being generated \\- The length of the key being generated The traffic keying material is generated from an input traffic secret value using: [sender]_write_key = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, \"key\", \"\", key_length) [sender]_write_iv = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, \"iv\", \"\", iv_length) [sender] denotes the sending side.",
            "Adjusted": "The traffic keying material is generated from the following input values: a secret value, a purpose value indicating the specific value being generated, and the length of the key being generated. The traffic keying material is generated from an input traffic secret value using: [sender]_write_key = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, \"key\", \"\", key_length) and [sender]_write_iv = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, \"iv\", \"\", iv_length). [sender] denotes the sending side."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of Secret for each record type is shown in the table below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "+-------------------+---------------------------------------+ | Record Type | Secret | +-------------------+---------------------------------------+ | 0-RTT Application | client_early_traffic_secret | | | | | Handshake | [sender]_handshake_traffic_secret | | | | | Application Data | [sender]_application_traffic_secret_N | +-------------------+---------------------------------------+ All the traffic keying material is recomputed whenever the underlying Secret changes (e.g., when changing from the handshake to Application Data keys or upon a key update).",
            "Adjusted": "The value of Secret for each record type is: for 0-RTT Application, client_early_traffic_secret; for Handshake, [sender]_handshake_traffic_secret; for Application Data, [sender]_application_traffic_secret_N. All the traffic keying material is recomputed whenever the underlying Secret changes, such as when changing from the handshake to Application Data keys or upon a key update."
        }
    ]
}

6. Alert Protocol -> 6.1. Closure Alerts:
{
    "6.1. Closure Alerts": [
        {
            "Original": "The client and the server must share knowledge that the connection is ending in order to avoid a truncation attack.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "close_notify: This alert notifies the recipient that the sender will not send any more messages on this connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any data received after a closure alert has been received MUST be ignored.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "user_canceled: This alert notifies the recipient that the sender is canceling the handshake for some reason unrelated to a protocol failure.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a user cancels an operation after the handshake is complete, just closing the connection by sending a \"close_notify\" is more appropriate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This alert SHOULD be followed by a \"close_notify\".",
            "Adjusted": "The user_canceled alert SHOULD be followed by a \"close_notify\"."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This alert generally has AlertLevel=warning.",
            "Adjusted": "The user_canceled alert generally has AlertLevel=warning."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Either party MAY initiate a close of its write side of the connection by sending a \"close_notify\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any data received after a closure alert has been received MUST be ignored.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a transport-level close is received prior to a \"close_notify\", the receiver cannot know that all the data that was sent has been received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each party MUST send a \"close_notify\" alert before closing its write side of the connection, unless it has already sent some error alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This does not have any effect on its read side of the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "Sending a \"close_notify\" alert does not have any effect on its read side of the connection."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that this is a change from versions of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 in which implementations were required to react to a \"close_notify\" by discarding pending writes and sending an immediate \"close_notify\" alert of their own.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that this requirement is a change from versions of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 in which implementations were required to react to a \"close_notify\" by discarding pending writes and sending an immediate \"close_notify\" alert of their own."
        },
        {
            "Original": "That previous requirement could cause truncation in the read side.",
            "Adjusted": "The previous requirement to react immediately to a \"close_notify\" could cause truncation in the read side."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both parties need not wait to receive a \"close_notify\" alert before closing their read side of the connection, though doing so would introduce the possibility of truncation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the application protocol using TLS provides that any data may be carried over the underlying transport after the TLS connection is closed, the TLS implementation MUST receive a \"close_notify\" alert before indicating end-of-data to the application layer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "No part of this standard should be taken to dictate the manner in which a usage profile for TLS manages its data transport, including when connections are opened or closed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: It is assumed that closing the write side of a connection reliably delivers pending data before destroying the transport.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

6. Alert Protocol:
{
    "6. Alert Protocol": [
        {
            "Original": "TLS provides an Alert content type to indicate closure information and errors.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Like other messages, alert messages are encrypted as specified by the current connection state.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alert messages convey a description of the alert and a legacy field that conveyed the severity level of the message in previous versions of TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alerts are divided into two classes: closure alerts and error alerts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS 1.3, the severity is implicit in the type of alert being sent, and the \"level\" field can safely be ignored.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"close_notify\" alert is used to indicate orderly closure of one direction of the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receiving such an alert, the TLS implementation SHOULD indicate end-of-data to the application.",
            "Adjusted": "Upon receiving a close_notify alert, the TLS implementation SHOULD indicate end-of-data to the application."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Error alerts indicate abortive closure of the connection (seeSection 6.2).",
            "Adjusted": "Error alerts indicate abortive closure of the connection (see Section 6.2)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receiving an error alert, the TLS implementation SHOULD indicate an error to the application and MUST NOT allow any further data to be sent or received on the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers and clients MUST forget the secret values and keys established in failed connections, with the exception of the PSKs associated with session tickets, which SHOULD be discarded if possible.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "All the alerts listed in Section 6.2 MUST be sent with AlertLevel=fatal and MUST be treated as error alerts when received regardless of the AlertLevel in the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unknown Alert types MUST be treated as error alerts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: TLS defines two generic alerts (see Section 6) to use upon failure to parse a message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Peers which receive a message which cannot be parsed according to the syntax (e.g., have a length extending beyond the message boundary or contain an out-of-range length) MUST terminate the connection with a \"decode_error\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Peers which receive a message which is syntactically correct but semantically invalid (e.g., a DHE share of p - 1, or an invalid enum) MUST terminate the connection with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "enum { warning(1), fatal(2), (255) } AlertLevel; enum { close_notify(0), unexpected_message(10), bad_record_mac(20), record_overflow(22), handshake_failure(40), bad_certificate(42), unsupported_certificate(43), certificate_revoked(44), certificate_expired(45), certificate_unknown(46), illegal_parameter(47), unknown_ca(48), access_denied(49), decode_error(50), decrypt_error(51), protocol_version(70), insufficient_security(71), internal_error(80), inappropriate_fallback(86), user_canceled(90), missing_extension(109), unsupported_extension(110), unrecognized_name(112), bad_certificate_status_response(113), unknown_psk_identity(115), certificate_required(116), no_application_protocol(120), (255) } AlertDescription; struct { AlertLevel level; AlertDescription description; } Alert;",
            "Adjusted": "The AlertLevel enumeration defines warning(1) and fatal(2) values. The AlertDescription enumeration includes various alert types such as close_notify(0), unexpected_message(10), bad_record_mac(20), record_overflow(22), handshake_failure(40), bad_certificate(42), unsupported_certificate(43), certificate_revoked(44), certificate_expired(45), certificate_unknown(46), illegal_parameter(47), unknown_ca(48), access_denied(49), decode_error(50), decrypt_error(51), protocol_version(70), insufficient_security(71), internal_error(80), inappropriate_fallback(86), user_canceled(90), missing_extension(109), unsupported_extension(110), unrecognized_name(112), bad_certificate_status_response(113), unknown_psk_identity(115), certificate_required(116), and no_application_protocol(120). The Alert structure consists of an AlertLevel level field and an AlertDescription description field."
        }
    ]
}

5. Record Protocol -> 5.1. Record Layer:
{
    "5. Record Protocol -> 5.1. Record Layer": [
        {
            "Original": "The record layer fragments information blocks into TLSPlaintext records carrying data in chunks of 2^14 bytes or less.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Message boundaries are handled differently depending on the underlying ContentType.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any future content types MUST specify appropriate rules.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that these rules are stricter than what was enforced in TLS 1.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Handshake messages MAY be coalesced into a single TLSPlaintext record or fragmented across several records, provided that: \\- Handshake messages MUST NOT be interleaved with other record types.",
            "Adjusted": "Handshake messages MAY be coalesced into a single TLSPlaintext record or fragmented across several records, provided that: Handshake messages MUST NOT be interleaved with other record types."
        },
        {
            "Original": "That is, if a handshake message is split over two or more records, there MUST NOT be any other records between them.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Handshake messages MUST NOT span key changes.",
            "Adjusted": "Handshake messages MUST NOT span key changes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST verify that all messages immediately preceding a key change align with a record boundary; if not, then they MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "Implementations MUST verify that all messages immediately preceding a key change align with a record boundary; if not, then implementations MUST terminate the connection with an \"unexpected_message\" alert."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because the ClientHello, EndOfEarlyData, ServerHello, Finished, and KeyUpdate messages can immediately precede a key change, implementations MUST send these messages in alignment with a record boundary.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST NOT send zero-length fragments of Handshake types, even if those fragments contain padding.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alert messages (Section 6) MUST NOT be fragmented across records, and multiple alert messages MUST NOT be coalesced into a single TLSPlaintext record.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In other words, a record with an Alert type MUST contain exactly one message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application Data messages contain data that is opaque to TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application Data messages are always protected.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Zero-length fragments of Application Data MAY be sent, as they are potentially useful as a traffic analysis countermeasure.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application Data fragments MAY be split across multiple records or coalesced into a single record.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "enum { invalid(0), change_cipher_spec(20), alert(21), handshake(22), application_data(23), (255) } ContentType; struct { ContentType type; ProtocolVersion legacy_record_version; uint16 length; opaque fragment[TLSPlaintext.length]; } TLSPlaintext; type: The higher-level protocol used to process the enclosed fragment.",
            "Adjusted": "ContentType is an enumeration with values: invalid(0), change_cipher_spec(20), alert(21), handshake(22), application_data(23), and (255). TLSPlaintext is a structure containing: type, which is the higher-level protocol used to process the enclosed fragment; legacy_record_version; length; and fragment."
        },
        {
            "Original": "legacy_record_version: MUST be set to 0x0303 for all records generated by a TLS 1.3 implementation other than an initial ClientHello (i.e., one not generated after a HelloRetryRequest), where it MAY also be 0x0301 for compatibility purposes.",
            "Adjusted": "legacy_record_version MUST be set to 0x0303 for all records generated by a TLS 1.3 implementation other than an initial ClientHello, which is one not generated after a HelloRetryRequest, where legacy_record_version MAY also be 0x0301 for compatibility purposes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This field is deprecated and MUST be ignored for all purposes.",
            "Adjusted": "The legacy_record_version field is deprecated and MUST be ignored for all purposes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Previous versions of TLS would use other values in this field under some circumstances.",
            "Adjusted": "Previous versions of TLS would use other values in the legacy_record_version field under some circumstances."
        },
        {
            "Original": "length: The length (in bytes) of the following TLSPlaintext.fragment.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length MUST NOT exceed 2^14 bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An endpoint that receives a record that exceeds this length MUST terminate the connection with a \"record_overflow\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "fragment: The data being transmitted.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This value is transparent and is treated as an independent block to be dealt with by the higher- level protocol specified by the type field.",
            "Adjusted": "The fragment value is transparent and is treated as an independent block to be dealt with by the higher-level protocol specified by the type field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document describes TLS 1.3, which uses the version 0x0304.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This version value is historical, deriving from the use of 0x0301 for TLS 1.0 and 0x0300 for SSL 3.0.",
            "Adjusted": "The version value 0x0304 is historical, deriving from the use of 0x0301 for TLS 1.0 and 0x0300 for SSL 3.0."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to maximize backward compatibility, a record containing an initial ClientHello SHOULD have version 0x0301 (reflecting TLS 1.0) and a record containing a second ClientHello or a ServerHello MUST have version 0x0303 (reflecting TLS 1.2).",
            "Adjusted": "In order to maximize backward compatibility, a record containing an initial ClientHello SHOULD have legacy_record_version 0x0301, reflecting TLS 1.0, and a record containing a second ClientHello or a ServerHello MUST have legacy_record_version 0x0303, reflecting TLS 1.2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When negotiating prior versions of TLS, endpoints follow the procedure and requirements provided in Appendix D.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When record protection has not yet been engaged, TLSPlaintext structures are written directly onto the wire.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once record protection has started, TLSPlaintext records are protected and sent as described in the following section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that Application Data records MUST NOT be written to the wire unprotected (see Section 2 for details).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay -> 8.1. Single-:
{
    "8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay -> 8.1. Single-Use Tickets": [
        {
            "Original": "The simplest form of anti-replay defense is for the server to only allow each session ticket to be used once.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For instance, the server can maintain a database of all outstanding valid tickets, deleting each ticket from the database as it is used.",
            "Adjusted": "For instance, the server can maintain a database of all outstanding valid tickets, deleting each ticket from the database as the ticket is used."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If an unknown ticket is provided, the server would then fall back to a full handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the tickets are not self-contained but rather are database keys, and the corresponding PSKs are deleted upon use, then connections established using PSKs enjoy forward secrecy.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This improves security for all 0-RTT data and PSK usage when PSK is used without (EC)DHE.",
            "Adjusted": "This mechanism improves security for all 0-RTT data and PSK usage when PSK is used without (EC)DHE."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because this mechanism requires sharing the session database between server nodes in environments with multiple distributed servers, it may be hard to achieve high rates of successful PSK 0-RTT connections when compared to self-encrypted tickets.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unlike session databases, session tickets can successfully do PSK-based session establishment even without consistent storage, though when 0-RTT is allowed they still require consistent storage for anti-replay of 0-RTT data, as detailed in the following section.",
            "Adjusted": "Unlike session databases, session tickets can successfully do PSK-based session establishment even without consistent storage, though when 0-RTT is allowed session tickets still require consistent storage for anti-replay of 0-RTT data, as detailed in the following section."
        }
    ]
}

9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.1. Manda:
{
    "9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.1. Mandatory-to-Implement Cipher Suites": [
        {
            "Original": "In the absence of an application profile standard specifying otherwise: A TLS-compliant application MUST implement the TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256 [GCM and GMAC\"\")] cipher suite and SHOULD implement the TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384 [GCM and GMAC\"\")] and TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256 [RFC8439] cipher suites (see Appendix B.4).",
            "Adjusted": "In the absence of an application profile standard specifying otherwise: A TLS-compliant application MUST implement the TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256 cipher suite and SHOULD implement the TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384 and TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256 cipher suites (see Appendix B.4)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A TLS-compliant application MUST support digital signatures with rsa_pkcs1_sha256 (for certificates), rsa_pss_rsae_sha256 (for CertificateVerify and certificates), and ecdsa_secp256r1_sha256.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A TLS-compliant application MUST support key exchange with secp256r1 (NIST P-256) and SHOULD support key exchange with X25519 [RFC7748].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.4. (E:
{
    "7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.4. (EC)DHE Shared Secret Calculation -> 7.4.2. Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman": [
        {
            "Original": "For secp256r1, secp384r1, and secp521r1, ECDH calculations (including parameter and key generation as well as the shared secret calculation) are performed according to [IEEE1363] using the ECKAS-DH1 scheme with the identity map as the key derivation function (KDF), so that the shared secret is the x-coordinate of the ECDH shared secret elliptic curve point represented as an octet string.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that this octet string (\"Z\" in IEEE 1363 terminology) as output by FE2OSP (the Field Element to Octet String Conversion Primitive) has constant length for any given field; leading zeros found in this octet string MUST NOT be truncated.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(Note that this use of the identity KDF is a technicality.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The complete picture is that ECDH is employed with a non-trivial KDF because TLS does not directly use this secret for anything other than for computing other secrets.) For X25519 and X448, the ECDH calculations are as follows: \\- The public key to put into the KeyShareEntry.key_exchange structure is the result of applying the ECDH scalar multiplication function to the secret key of appropriate length (into scalar input) and the standard public basepoint (into u-coordinate point input).",
            "Adjusted": "The complete picture is that ECDH is employed with a non-trivial KDF because TLS does not directly use the shared secret for anything other than for computing other secrets. For X25519 and X448, the ECDH calculations are as follows: The public key to put into the KeyShareEntry.key_exchange structure is the result of applying the ECDH scalar multiplication function to the secret key of appropriate length (into scalar input) and the standard public basepoint (into u-coordinate point input)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The ECDH shared secret is the result of applying the ECDH scalar multiplication function to the secret key (into scalar input) and the peer's public key (into u-coordinate point input).",
            "Adjusted": "The ECDH shared secret is the result of applying the ECDH scalar multiplication function to the secret key (into scalar input) and the peer's public key (into u-coordinate point input)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The output is used raw, with no processing.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For these curves, implementations SHOULD use the approach specified in [RFC7748] to calculate the Diffie-Hellman shared secret.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST check whether the computed Diffie-Hellman shared secret is the all-zero value and abort if so, as described in [Section 6 of [RFC7748]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7748#section-6).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If implementors use an alternative implementation of these elliptic curves, they SHOULD perform the additional checks specified in [Section 7 of [RFC7748]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7748#section-7).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.5. Ex:
{
    "7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.5. Exporters": [
        {
            "Original": "[RFC5705] defines keying material exporters for TLS in terms of the TLS pseudorandom function (PRF).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document replaces the PRF with HKDF, thus requiring a new construction.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The exporter interface remains the same.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The exporter value is computed as: TLS-Exporter(label, context_value, key_length) = HKDF-Expand-Label(Derive-Secret(Secret, label, \"\"), \"exporter\", Hash(context_value), key_length) Where Secret is either the early_exporter_master_secret or the exporter_master_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "The exporter value is computed as: TLS-Exporter(label, context_value, key_length) = HKDF-Expand-Label(Derive-Secret(Secret, label, \"\"), \"exporter\", Hash(context_value), key_length) where Secret is either the early_exporter_master_secret or the exporter_master_secret."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Implementations MUST use the exporter_master_secret unless explicitly specified by the application.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The early_exporter_master_secret is defined for use in settings where an exporter is needed for 0-RTT data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A separate interface for the early exporter is RECOMMENDED; this avoids the exporter user accidentally using an early exporter when a regular one is desired or vice versa.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If no context is provided, the context_value is zero length.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Consequently, providing no context computes the same value as providing an empty context.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is a change from previous versions of TLS where an empty context produced a different output than an absent context.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As of this document's publication, no allocated exporter label is used both with and without a context.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Future specifications MUST NOT define a use of exporters that permit both an empty context and no context with the same label.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "New uses of exporters SHOULD provide a context in all exporter computations, though the value could be empty.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Requirements for the format of exporter labels are defined in [Section 4 of [RFC5705]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5705#section-4).",
            "Adjusted": "Requirements for the format of exporter labels are defined in Section 4 of RFC5705."
        }
    ]
}

