4. Handshake Protocol -> 4.6. Post-Hands:
{
    "4.6.1. New Session Ticket Message": [
        {
            "Original": "At any time after the server has received the client Finished message, it MAY send a NewSessionTicket message.",
            "Adjusted": "At any time after the server has received the client Finished message, the server MAY send a NewSessionTicket message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message creates a unique association between the ticket value and a secret PSK derived from the resumption master secret (seeSection 7).",
            "Adjusted": "The NewSessionTicket message creates a unique association between the ticket value and a secret PSK derived from the resumption master secret (see Section 7)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY use this PSK for future handshakes by including the ticket value in the \"pre_shared_key\" extension in its ClientHello (Section 4.2.11).",
            "Adjusted": "The client MAY use the PSK derived from the ticket for future handshakes by including the ticket value in the \"pre_shared_key\" extension in its ClientHello (Section 4.2.11)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MAY send multiple tickets on a single connection, either immediately after each other or after specific events (see Appendix C.4).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For instance, the server might send a new ticket after post-handshake authentication in order to encapsulate the additional client authentication state.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Multiple tickets are useful for clients for a variety of purposes, including: \\- Opening multiple parallel HTTP connections.",
            "Adjusted": "Multiple tickets are useful for clients for a variety of purposes, including opening multiple parallel HTTP connections."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Performing connection racing across interfaces and address families via (for example) Happy Eyeballs [RFC8305] or related techniques.",
            "Adjusted": "Performing connection racing across interfaces and address families via (for example) Happy Eyeballs [RFC8305] or related techniques."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any ticket MUST only be resumed with a cipher suite that has the same KDF hash algorithm as that used to establish the original connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST only resume if the new SNI value is valid for the server certificate presented in the original session and SHOULD only resume if the SNI value matches the one used in the original session.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The latter is a performance optimization: normally, there is no reason to expect that different servers covered by a single certificate would be able to accept each other's tickets; hence, attempting resumption in that case would waste a single-use ticket.",
            "Adjusted": "The requirement to match the SNI value is a performance optimization: normally, there is no reason to expect that different servers covered by a single certificate would be able to accept each other's tickets; hence, attempting resumption in that case would waste a single-use ticket."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If such an indication is provided (externally or by any other means), clients MAY resume with a different SNI value.",
            "Adjusted": "If an indication is provided that different servers covered by a single certificate can accept each other's tickets (externally or by any other means), clients MAY resume with a different SNI value."
        },
        {
            "Original": "On resumption, if reporting an SNI value to the calling application, implementations MUST use the value sent in the resumption ClientHello rather than the value sent in the previous session.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that if a server implementation declines all PSK identities with different SNI values, these two values are always the same.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: Although the resumption master secret depends on the client's second flight, a server which does not request client authentication MAY compute the remainder of the transcript independently and then send a NewSessionTicket immediately upon sending its Finished rather than waiting for the client Finished.",
            "Adjusted": "Although the resumption master secret depends on the client's second flight, a server which does not request client authentication MAY compute the remainder of the transcript independently and then send a NewSessionTicket immediately upon sending its Finished rather than waiting for the client Finished."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This might be appropriate in cases where the client is expected to open multiple TLS connections in parallel and would benefit from the reduced overhead of a resumption handshake, for example.",
            "Adjusted": "Sending NewSessionTicket immediately might be appropriate in cases where the client is expected to open multiple TLS connections in parallel and would benefit from the reduced overhead of a resumption handshake, for example."
        },
        {
            "Original": "struct { uint32 ticket_lifetime; uint32 ticket_age_add; opaque ticket_nonce<0..255>; opaque ticket<1..2^16-1>; Extension extensions<0..2^16-2>; } NewSessionTicket; ticket_lifetime: Indicates the lifetime in seconds as a 32-bit unsigned integer in network byte order from the time of ticket issuance.",
            "Adjusted": "The NewSessionTicket structure contains: ticket_lifetime indicates the lifetime in seconds as a 32-bit unsigned integer in network byte order from the time of ticket issuance."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MUST NOT use any value greater than 604800 seconds (7 days).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of zero indicates that the ticket should be discarded immediately.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients MUST NOT cache tickets for longer than 7 days, regardless of the ticket_lifetime, and MAY delete tickets earlier based on local policy.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server MAY treat a ticket as valid for a shorter period of time than what is stated in the ticket_lifetime.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "ticket_age_add: A securely generated, random 32-bit value that is used to obscure the age of the ticket that the client includes in the \"pre_shared_key\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "ticket_age_add is a securely generated, random 32-bit value that is used to obscure the age of the ticket that the client includes in the \"pre_shared_key\" extension."
