5. Record Protocol -> 5.2. Record Payloa:
{
    "5. Record Protocol -> 5.2. Record Payload Protection": [
        {
            "Original": "The record protection functions translate a TLSPlaintext structure into a TLSCiphertext structure.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The deprotection functions reverse the process.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In TLS 1.3, as opposed to previous versions of TLS, all ciphers are modeled as \"Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data\" (AEAD) [RFC5116].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "AEAD functions provide a unified encryption and authentication operation which turns plaintext into authenticated ciphertext and back again.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each encrypted record consists of a plaintext header followed by an encrypted body, which itself contains a type and optional padding.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "struct { opaque content[TLSPlaintext.length]; ContentType type; uint8 zeros[length_of_padding]; } TLSInnerPlaintext; struct { ContentType opaque_type = application_data; /* 23 */ ProtocolVersion legacy_record_version = 0x0303; /* TLS v1.2 */ uint16 length; opaque encrypted_record[TLSCiphertext.length]; } TLSCiphertext; content: The TLSPlaintext.fragment value, containing the byte encoding of a handshake or an alert message, or the raw bytes of the application's data to send.",
            "Adjusted": "The TLSInnerPlaintext structure contains content, type, and zeros fields. The TLSCiphertext structure contains opaque_type, legacy_record_version, length, and encrypted_record fields. The content field contains the TLSPlaintext.fragment value, which holds the byte encoding of a handshake or an alert message, or the raw bytes of the application's data to send."
        },
        {
            "Original": "type: The TLSPlaintext.type value containing the content type of the record.",
            "Adjusted": "The type field contains the TLSPlaintext.type value, which specifies the content type of the record."
        },
        {
            "Original": "zeros: An arbitrary-length run of zero-valued bytes may appear in the cleartext after the type field.",
            "Adjusted": "The zeros field is an arbitrary-length run of zero-valued bytes that may appear in the cleartext after the type field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This provides an opportunity for senders to pad any TLS record by a chosen amount as long as the total stays within record size limits.",
            "Adjusted": "The zeros field provides an opportunity for senders to pad any TLS record by a chosen amount as long as the total stays within record size limits."
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Section 5.4 for more details.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "opaque_type: The outer opaque_type field of a TLSCiphertext record is always set to the value 23 (application_data) for outward compatibility with middleboxes accustomed to parsing previous versions of TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "The opaque_type field of a TLSCiphertext record is always set to the value 23 (application_data) for outward compatibility with middleboxes accustomed to parsing previous versions of TLS."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The actual content type of the record is found in TLSInnerPlaintext.type after decryption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "legacy_record_version: The legacy_record_version field is always 0x0303.",
            "Adjusted": "The legacy_record_version field is always 0x0303."
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS 1.3 TLSCiphertexts are not generated until after TLS 1.3 has been negotiated, so there are no historical compatibility concerns where other values might be received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the handshake protocol, including the ClientHello and ServerHello messages, authenticates the protocol version, so this value is redundant.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that the handshake protocol, including the ClientHello and ServerHello messages, authenticates the protocol version, so the legacy_record_version field is redundant."
        },
        {
            "Original": "length: The length (in bytes) of the following TLSCiphertext.encrypted_record, which is the sum of the lengths of the content and the padding, plus one for the inner content type, plus any expansion added by the AEAD algorithm.",
            "Adjusted": "The length field specifies the length in bytes of the following TLSCiphertext.encrypted_record, which is the sum of the lengths of the content and the padding, plus one for the inner content type, plus any expansion added by the AEAD algorithm."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length MUST NOT exceed 2^14 + 256 bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An endpoint that receives a record that exceeds this length MUST terminate the connection with a \"record_overflow\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "encrypted_record: The AEAD-encrypted form of the serialized TLSInnerPlaintext structure.",
            "Adjusted": "The encrypted_record field contains the AEAD-encrypted form of the serialized TLSInnerPlaintext structure."
        },
        {
            "Original": "AEAD algorithms take as input a single key, a nonce, a plaintext, and \"additional data\" to be included in the authentication check, as described in [Section 2.1 of [RFC5116]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5116#section-2.1).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The key is either the client_write_key or the server_write_key, the nonce is derived from the sequence number and the client_write_iv or server_write_iv (see Section 5.3), and the additional data input is the record header.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "I.e., additional_data = TLSCiphertext.opaque_type || TLSCiphertext.legacy_record_version || TLSCiphertext.length The plaintext input to the AEAD algorithm is the encoded TLSInnerPlaintext structure.",
            "Adjusted": "The additional data is TLSCiphertext.opaque_type concatenated with TLSCiphertext.legacy_record_version and TLSCiphertext.length. The plaintext input to the AEAD algorithm is the encoded TLSInnerPlaintext structure."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Derivation of traffic keys is defined in Section 7.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The AEAD output consists of the ciphertext output from the AEAD encryption operation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length of the plaintext is greater than the corresponding TLSPlaintext.length due to the inclusion of TLSInnerPlaintext.type and any padding supplied by the sender.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The length of the AEAD output will generally be larger than the plaintext, but by an amount that varies with the AEAD algorithm.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Since the ciphers might incorporate padding, the amount of overhead could vary with different lengths of plaintext.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Symbolically, AEADEncrypted = AEAD-Encrypt(write_key, nonce, additional_data, plaintext) The encrypted_record field of TLSCiphertext is set to AEADEncrypted.",
            "Adjusted": "Symbolically, AEADEncrypted = AEAD-Encrypt(write_key, nonce, additional_data, plaintext). The encrypted_record field of TLSCiphertext is set to AEADEncrypted."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to decrypt and verify, the cipher takes as input the key, nonce, additional data, and the AEADEncrypted value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The output is either the plaintext or an error indicating that the decryption failed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There is no separate integrity check.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Symbolically, plaintext of encrypted_record = AEAD-Decrypt(peer_write_key, nonce, additional_data, AEADEncrypted) If the decryption fails, the receiver MUST terminate the connection with a \"bad_record_mac\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "Symbolically, plaintext of encrypted_record = AEAD-Decrypt(peer_write_key, nonce, additional_data, AEADEncrypted). If the decryption fails, the receiver MUST terminate the connection with a \"bad_record_mac\" alert."
        },
        {
            "Original": "An AEAD algorithm used in TLS 1.3 MUST NOT produce an expansion greater than 255 octets.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An endpoint that receives a record from its peer with TLSCiphertext.length larger than 2^14 + 256 octets MUST terminate the connection with a \"record_overflow\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This limit is derived from the maximum TLSInnerPlaintext length of 2^14 octets + 1 octet for ContentType + the maximum AEAD expansion of 255 octets.",
            "Adjusted": "The 2^14 + 256 octets limit is derived from the maximum TLSInnerPlaintext length of 2^14 octets plus 1 octet for ContentType plus the maximum AEAD expansion of 255 octets."
        }
    ]
}

8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay -> 8.3. Freshne:
{
    "8.3. Freshness Checks": [
        {
            "Original": "Because the ClientHello indicates the time at which the client sent it, it is possible to efficiently determine whether a ClientHello was likely sent reasonably recently and only accept 0-RTT for such a ClientHello, otherwise falling back to a 1-RTT handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "Because the ClientHello indicates the time at which the client sent the ClientHello, it is possible to efficiently determine whether a ClientHello was likely sent reasonably recently and only accept 0-RTT for such a ClientHello, otherwise falling back to a 1-RTT handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is necessary for the ClientHello storage mechanism described inSection 8.2 because otherwise the server needs to store an unlimited number of ClientHellos, and is a useful optimization for self- contained single-use tickets because it allows efficient rejection of ClientHellos which cannot be used for 0-RTT.",
            "Adjusted": "This freshness checking mechanism is necessary for the ClientHello storage mechanism described in Section 8.2 because otherwise the server needs to store an unlimited number of ClientHellos, and is a useful optimization for self-contained single-use tickets because the mechanism allows efficient rejection of ClientHellos which cannot be used for 0-RTT."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to implement this mechanism, a server needs to store the time that the server generated the session ticket, offset by an estimate of the round-trip time between client and server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "I.e., adjusted_creation_time = creation_time + estimated_RTT This value can be encoded in the ticket, thus avoiding the need to keep state for each outstanding ticket.",
            "Adjusted": "For example, adjusted_creation_time equals creation_time plus estimated_RTT. This value can be encoded in the ticket, thus avoiding the need to keep state for each outstanding ticket."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server can determine the client's view of the age of the ticket by subtracting the ticket's \"ticket_age_add\" value from the \"obfuscated_ticket_age\" parameter in the client's \"pre_shared_key\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server can determine the expected_arrival_time of the ClientHello as: expected_arrival_time = adjusted_creation_time + clients_ticket_age When a new ClientHello is received, the expected_arrival_time is then compared against the current server wall clock time and if they differ by more than a certain amount, 0-RTT is rejected, though the 1-RTT handshake can be allowed to complete.",
            "Adjusted": "The server can determine the expected_arrival_time of the ClientHello as: expected_arrival_time equals adjusted_creation_time plus clients_ticket_age. When a new ClientHello is received, the expected_arrival_time is then compared against the current server wall clock time and if the times differ by more than a certain amount, 0-RTT is rejected, though the 1-RTT handshake can be allowed to complete."
        },
        {
            "Original": "There are several potential sources of error that might cause mismatches between the expected_arrival_time and the measured time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Variations in client and server clock rates are likely to be minimal, though potentially the absolute times may be off by large values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Network propagation delays are the most likely causes of a mismatch in legitimate values for elapsed time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both the NewSessionTicket and ClientHello messages might be retransmitted and therefore delayed, which might be hidden by TCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For clients on the Internet, this implies windows on the order of ten seconds to account for errors in clocks and variations in measurements; other deployment scenarios may have different needs.",
            "Adjusted": "For clients on the Internet, this freshness checking mechanism implies windows on the order of ten seconds to account for errors in clocks and variations in measurements; other deployment scenarios may have different needs."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clock skew distributions are not symmetric, so the optimal tradeoff may involve an asymmetric range of permissible mismatch values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that freshness checking alone is not sufficient to prevent replays because it does not detect them during the error window, which -- depending on bandwidth and system capacity -- could include billions of replays in real-world settings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, this freshness checking is only done at the time the ClientHello is received and not when subsequent early Application Data records are received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "After early data is accepted, records may continue to be streamed to the server over a longer time period.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay:
{
    "0-RTT and Anti-Replay": [
        {
            "Original": "As noted inSection 2.3 and Appendix E.5, TLS does not provide inherent replay protections for 0-RTT data.",
            "Adjusted": "As noted in Section 2.3 and Appendix E.5, TLS does not provide inherent replay protections for 0-RTT data."
        },
        {
            "Original": "There are two potential threats to be concerned with: \\- Network attackers who mount a replay attack by simply duplicating a flight of 0-RTT data.",
            "Adjusted": "There are two potential threats to be concerned with: Network attackers who mount a replay attack by simply duplicating a flight of 0-RTT data."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Network attackers who take advantage of client retry behavior to arrange for the server to receive multiple copies of an application message.",
            "Adjusted": "Network attackers who take advantage of client retry behavior to arrange for the server to receive multiple copies of an application message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This threat already exists to some extent because clients that value robustness respond to network errors by attempting to retry requests.",
            "Adjusted": "This threat already exists to some extent because clients that value robustness respond to network errors by attempting to retry requests."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, 0-RTT adds an additional dimension for any server system which does not maintain globally consistent server state.",
            "Adjusted": "However, 0-RTT adds an additional dimension for any server system which does not maintain globally consistent server state."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specifically, if a server system has multiple zones where tickets from zone A will not be accepted in zone B, then an attacker can duplicate a ClientHello and early data intended for A to both A and B.",
            "Adjusted": "Specifically, if a server system has multiple zones where tickets from zone A will not be accepted in zone B, then an attacker can duplicate a ClientHello and early data intended for A to both A and B."
        },
        {
            "Original": "At A, the data will be accepted in 0-RTT, but at B the server will reject 0-RTT data and instead force a full handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "At A, the data will be accepted in 0-RTT, but at B the server will reject 0-RTT data and instead force a full handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the attacker blocks the ServerHello from A, then the client will complete the handshake with B and probably retry the request, leading to duplication on the server system as a whole.",
            "Adjusted": "If the attacker blocks the ServerHello from A, then the client will complete the handshake with B and probably retry the request, leading to duplication on the server system as a whole."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The first class of attack can be prevented by sharing state to guarantee that the 0-RTT data is accepted at most once.",
            "Adjusted": "The first class of attack can be prevented by sharing state to guarantee that the 0-RTT data is accepted at most once."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers SHOULD provide that level of replay safety by implementing one of the methods described in this section or by equivalent means.",
            "Adjusted": "Servers SHOULD provide that level of replay safety by implementing one of the methods described in this section or by equivalent means."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is understood, however, that due to operational concerns not all deployments will maintain state at that level.",
            "Adjusted": "It is understood, however, that due to operational concerns not all deployments will maintain state at that level."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Therefore, in normal operation, clients will not know which, if any, of these mechanisms servers actually implement and hence MUST only send early data which they deem safe to be replayed.",
            "Adjusted": "Therefore, in normal operation, clients will not know which, if any, of these mechanisms servers actually implement and hence MUST only send early data which they deem safe to be replayed."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition to the direct effects of replays, there is a class of attacks where even operations normally considered idempotent could be exploited by a large number of replays (timing attacks, resource limit exhaustion and others, as described in Appendix E.5).",
            "Adjusted": "In addition to the direct effects of replays, there is a class of attacks where even operations normally considered idempotent could be exploited by a large number of replays (timing attacks, resource limit exhaustion and others, as described in Appendix E.5)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Those can be mitigated by ensuring that every 0-RTT payload can be replayed only a limited number of times.",
            "Adjusted": "Those attacks can be mitigated by ensuring that every 0-RTT payload can be replayed only a limited number of times."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST ensure that any instance of it (be it a machine, a thread, or any other entity within the relevant serving infrastructure) would accept 0-RTT for the same 0-RTT handshake at most once; this limits the number of replays to the number of server instances in the deployment.",
            "Adjusted": "The server MUST ensure that any instance of the server (be it a machine, a thread, or any other entity within the relevant serving infrastructure) would accept 0-RTT for the same 0-RTT handshake at most once; this limits the number of replays to the number of server instances in the deployment."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Such a guarantee can be accomplished by locally recording data from recently received ClientHellos and rejecting repeats, or by any other method that provides the same or a stronger guarantee.",
            "Adjusted": "Such a guarantee can be accomplished by locally recording data from recently received ClientHellos and rejecting repeats, or by any other method that provides the same or a stronger guarantee."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The \"at most once per server instance\" guarantee is a minimum requirement; servers SHOULD limit 0-RTT replays further when feasible.",
            "Adjusted": "The \"at most once per server instance\" guarantee is a minimum requirement; servers SHOULD limit 0-RTT replays further when feasible."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The second class of attack cannot be prevented at the TLS layer and MUST be dealt with by any application.",
            "Adjusted": "The second class of attack cannot be prevented at the TLS layer and MUST be dealt with by any application."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that any application whose clients implement any kind of retry behavior already needs to implement some sort of anti-replay defense.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that any application whose clients implement any kind of retry behavior already needs to implement some sort of anti-replay defense."
        }
    ]
}

6. Alert Protocol -> 6.2. Error Alerts:
{
    "6.2. Error Alerts": [
        {
            "Original": "Error handling in TLS is very simple.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When an error is detected, the detecting party sends a message to its peer.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon transmission or receipt of a fatal alert message, both parties MUST immediately close the connection.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Whenever an implementation encounters a fatal error condition, it SHOULD send an appropriate fatal alert and MUST close the connection without sending or receiving any additional data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the rest of this specification, when the phrases \"terminate the connection\" and \"abort the handshake\" are used without a specific alert it means that the implementation SHOULD send the alert indicated by the descriptions below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The phrases \"terminate the connection with an X alert\" and \"abort the handshake with an X alert\" mean that the implementation MUST send alert X if it sends any alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "All alerts defined below in this section, as well as all unknown alerts, are universally considered fatal as of TLS 1.3 (seeSection 6).",
            "Adjusted": "All alerts defined below in this section, as well as all unknown alerts, are universally considered fatal as of TLS 1.3 (see Section 6)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The implementation SHOULD provide a way to facilitate logging the sending and receiving of alerts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
