9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.2. Manda:
{
    "9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.2. Mandatory-to-Implement Extensions": [
        {
            "Original": "In the absence of an application profile standard specifying otherwise, a TLS-compliant application MUST implement the following TLS extensions: \\- Supported Versions (\"supported_versions\";Section 4.2.1) \\- Cookie (\"cookie\"; Section 4.2.2) \\- Signature Algorithms (\"signature_algorithms\"; Section 4.2.3) \\- Signature Algorithms Certificate (\"signature_algorithms_cert\"; Section 4.2.3) \\- Negotiated Groups (\"supported_groups\"; Section 4.2.7) \\- Key Share (\"key_share\"; Section 4.2.8) \\- Server Name Indication (\"server_name\"; [Section 3 of [RFC6066]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6066#section-3)) All implementations MUST send and use these extensions when offering applicable features: \\- \"supported_versions\" is REQUIRED for all ClientHello, ServerHello, and HelloRetryRequest messages.",
            "Adjusted": "In the absence of an application profile standard specifying otherwise, a TLS-compliant application MUST implement the following TLS extensions: Supported Versions (\"supported_versions\"; Section 4.2.1), Cookie (\"cookie\"; Section 4.2.2), Signature Algorithms (\"signature_algorithms\"; Section 4.2.3), Signature Algorithms Certificate (\"signature_algorithms_cert\"; Section 4.2.3), Negotiated Groups (\"supported_groups\"; Section 4.2.7), Key Share (\"key_share\"; Section 4.2.8), and Server Name Indication (\"server_name\"; Section 3 of RFC6066). All implementations MUST send and use these extensions when offering applicable features: \"supported_versions\" is REQUIRED for all ClientHello, ServerHello, and HelloRetryRequest messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"signature_algorithms\" is REQUIRED for certificate authentication.",
            "Adjusted": "\"signature_algorithms\" is REQUIRED for certificate authentication."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"supported_groups\" is REQUIRED for ClientHello messages using DHE or ECDHE key exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "\"supported_groups\" is REQUIRED for ClientHello messages using DHE or ECDHE key exchange."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"key_share\" is REQUIRED for DHE or ECDHE key exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "\"key_share\" is REQUIRED for DHE or ECDHE key exchange."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"pre_shared_key\" is REQUIRED for PSK key agreement.",
            "Adjusted": "\"pre_shared_key\" is REQUIRED for PSK key agreement."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"psk_key_exchange_modes\" is REQUIRED for PSK key agreement.",
            "Adjusted": "\"psk_key_exchange_modes\" is REQUIRED for PSK key agreement."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client is considered to be attempting to negotiate using this specification if the ClientHello contains a \"supported_versions\" extension with 0x0304 contained in its body.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Such a ClientHello message MUST meet the following requirements: \\- If not containing a \"pre_shared_key\" extension, it MUST contain both a \"signature_algorithms\" extension and a \"supported_groups\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "Such a ClientHello message MUST meet the following requirements: If not containing a \"pre_shared_key\" extension, it MUST contain both a \"signature_algorithms\" extension and a \"supported_groups\" extension."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- If containing a \"supported_groups\" extension, it MUST also contain a \"key_share\" extension, and vice versa.",
            "Adjusted": "If containing a \"supported_groups\" extension, it MUST also contain a \"key_share\" extension, and vice versa."
        },
        {
            "Original": "An empty KeyShare.client_shares vector is permitted.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers receiving a ClientHello which does not conform to these requirements MUST abort the handshake with a \"missing_extension\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additionally, all implementations MUST support the use of the \"server_name\" extension with applications capable of using it.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MAY require clients to send a valid \"server_name\" extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers requiring this extension SHOULD respond to a ClientHello lacking a \"server_name\" extension by terminating the connection with a \"missing_extension\" alert.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay -> 8.2. Client:
{
    "8. 0-RTT and Anti-Replay -> 8.2. Client Hello Recording": [
        {
            "Original": "An alternative form of anti-replay is to record a unique value derived from the ClientHello (generally either the random value or the PSK binder) and reject duplicates.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Recording all ClientHellos causes state to grow without bound, but a server can instead record ClientHellos within a given time window and use the \"obfuscated_ticket_age\" to ensure that tickets aren't reused outside that window.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to implement this, when a ClientHello is received, the server first verifies the PSK binder as described inSection 4.2.11.",
            "Adjusted": "In order to implement this, when a ClientHello is received, the server first verifies the PSK binder as described in Section 4.2.11."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It then computes the expected_arrival_time as described in the next section and rejects 0-RTT if it is outside the recording window, falling back to the 1-RTT handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "The server then computes the expected_arrival_time as described in the next section and rejects 0-RTT if the expected_arrival_time is outside the recording window, falling back to the 1-RTT handshake."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the expected_arrival_time is in the window, then the server checks to see if it has recorded a matching ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If one is found, it either aborts the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert or accepts the PSK but rejects 0-RTT.",
            "Adjusted": "If a matching ClientHello is found, the server either aborts the handshake with an \"illegal_parameter\" alert or accepts the PSK but rejects 0-RTT."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If no matching ClientHello is found, then it accepts 0-RTT and then stores the ClientHello for as long as the expected_arrival_time is inside the window.",
            "Adjusted": "If no matching ClientHello is found, then the server accepts 0-RTT and then stores the ClientHello for as long as the expected_arrival_time is inside the window."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers MAY also implement data stores with false positives, such as Bloom filters, in which case they MUST respond to apparent replay by rejecting 0-RTT but MUST NOT abort the handshake.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST derive the storage key only from validated sections of the ClientHello.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the ClientHello contains multiple PSK identities, then an attacker can create multiple ClientHellos with different binder values for the less-preferred identity on the assumption that the server will not verify it (as recommended by Section 4.2.11).",
            "Adjusted": "If the ClientHello contains multiple PSK identities, then an attacker can create multiple ClientHellos with different binder values for the less-preferred identity on the assumption that the server will not verify the less-preferred identity (as recommended by Section 4.2.11)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "I.e., if the client sends PSKs A and B but the server prefers A, then the attacker can change the binder for B without affecting the binder for A.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the binder for B is part of the storage key, then this ClientHello will not appear as a duplicate, which will cause the ClientHello to be accepted, and may cause side effects such as replay cache pollution, although any 0-RTT data will not be decryptable because it will use different keys.",
            "Adjusted": "If the binder for B is part of the storage key, then this ClientHello will not appear as a duplicate, which will cause the ClientHello to be accepted, and may cause side effects such as replay cache pollution, although any 0-RTT data will not be decryptable because the data will use different keys."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the validated binder or the ClientHello.random is used as the storage key, then this attack is not possible.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because this mechanism does not require storing all outstanding tickets, it may be easier to implement in distributed systems with high rates of resumption and 0-RTT, at the cost of potentially weaker anti-replay defense because of the difficulty of reliably storing and retrieving the received ClientHello messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In many such systems, it is impractical to have globally consistent storage of all the received ClientHellos.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, the best anti-replay protection is provided by having a single storage zone be authoritative for a given ticket and refusing 0-RTT for that ticket in any other zone.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This approach prevents simple replay by the attacker because only one zone will accept 0-RTT data.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A weaker design is to implement separate storage for each zone but allow 0-RTT in any zone.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This approach limits the number of replays to once per zone.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Application message duplication of course remains possible with either design.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When implementations are freshly started, they SHOULD reject 0-RTT as long as any portion of their recording window overlaps the startup time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise, they run the risk of accepting replays which were originally sent during that period.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: If the client's clock is running much faster than the server's, then a ClientHello may be received that is outside the window in the future, in which case it might be accepted for 1-RTT, causing a client retry, and then acceptable later for 0-RTT.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client's clock is running much faster than the server's, then a ClientHello may be received that is outside the window in the future, in which case the ClientHello might be accepted for 1-RTT, causing a client retry, and then acceptable later for 0-RTT."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is another variant of the second form of attack described in Section 8.",
            "Adjusted": "This scenario is another variant of the second form of attack described in Section 8."
        }
    ]
}

7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.1. Ke:
{
    "7. Cryptographic Computations -> 7.1. Key Schedule": [
        {
            "Original": "The key derivation process makes use of the HKDF-Extract and HKDF-Expand functions as defined for HKDF [RFC5869\"\")], as well as the functions defined below: HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, Label, Context, Length) = HKDF-Expand(Secret, HkdfLabel, Length) Where HkdfLabel is specified as: struct { uint16 length = Length; opaque label<7..255> = \"tls13 \" + Label; opaque context<0..255> = Context; } HkdfLabel; Derive-Secret(Secret, Label, Messages) = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, Label, Transcript-Hash(Messages), Hash.length) The Hash function used by Transcript-Hash and HKDF is the cipher suite hash algorithm.",
            "Adjusted": "The key derivation process makes use of the HKDF-Extract and HKDF-Expand functions as defined for HKDF [RFC5869], as well as the functions defined below: HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, Label, Context, Length) = HKDF-Expand(Secret, HkdfLabel, Length) where HkdfLabel is specified as: struct { uint16 length = Length; opaque label<7..255> = \"tls13 \" + Label; opaque context<0..255> = Context; } HkdfLabel; Derive-Secret(Secret, Label, Messages) = HKDF-Expand-Label(Secret, Label, Transcript-Hash(Messages), Hash.length). The Hash function used by Transcript-Hash and HKDF is the cipher suite hash algorithm."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Hash.length is its output length in bytes.",
            "Adjusted": "Hash.length is the output length of the Hash function in bytes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Messages is the concatenation of the indicated handshake messages, including the handshake message type and length fields, but not including record layer headers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that in some cases a zero- length Context (indicated by \"\") is passed to HKDF-Expand-Label.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The labels specified in this document are all ASCII strings and do not include a trailing NUL byte.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note: With common hash functions, any label longer than 12 characters requires an additional iteration of the hash function to compute.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The labels in this specification have all been chosen to fit within this limit.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Keys are derived from two input secrets using the HKDF-Extract and Derive-Secret functions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The general pattern for adding a new secret is to use HKDF-Extract with the Salt being the current secret state and the Input Keying Material (IKM) being the new secret to be added.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this version of TLS 1.3, the two input secrets are: \\- PSK (a pre-shared key established externally or derived from the resumption_master_secret value from a previous connection) \\- (EC)DHE shared secret (Section 7.4) This produces a full key derivation schedule shown in the diagram below.",
            "Adjusted": "In this version of TLS 1.3, the two input secrets are: PSK (a pre-shared key established externally or derived from the resumption_master_secret value from a previous connection) and (EC)DHE shared secret (Section 7.4). This produces a full key derivation schedule shown in the diagram below."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this diagram, the following formatting conventions apply: \\- HKDF-Extract is drawn as taking the Salt argument from the top and the IKM argument from the left, with its output to the bottom and the name of the output on the right.",
            "Adjusted": "In this diagram, the following formatting conventions apply: HKDF-Extract is drawn as taking the Salt argument from the top and the IKM argument from the left, with its output to the bottom and the name of the output on the right."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Derive-Secret's Secret argument is indicated by the incoming arrow.",
            "Adjusted": "Derive-Secret's Secret argument is indicated by the incoming arrow."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For instance, the Early Secret is the Secret for generating the client_early_traffic_secret.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- \"0\" indicates a string of Hash.length bytes set to zero.",
            "Adjusted": "\"0\" indicates a string of Hash.length bytes set to zero."
        },
        {
            "Original": "0 | v PSK -> HKDF-Extract = Early Secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"ext binder\" | \"res binder\", \"\") | = binder_key | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"c e traffic\", ClientHello) | = client_early_traffic_secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"e exp master\", ClientHello) | = early_exporter_master_secret v Derive-Secret(., \"derived\", \"\") | v (EC)DHE -> HKDF-Extract = Handshake Secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"c hs traffic\", | ClientHello...ServerHello) | = client_handshake_traffic_secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"s hs traffic\", | ClientHello...ServerHello) | = server_handshake_traffic_secret v Derive-Secret(., \"derived\", \"\") | v 0 -> HKDF-Extract = Master Secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"c ap traffic\", | ClientHello...server Finished) | = client_application_traffic_secret_0 | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"s ap traffic\", | ClientHello...server Finished) | = server_application_traffic_secret_0 | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"exp master\", | ClientHello...server Finished) | = exporter_master_secret | +-----> Derive-Secret(., \"res master\", ClientHello...client Finished) = resumption_master_secret The general pattern here is that the secrets shown down the left side of the diagram are just raw entropy without context, whereas the secrets down the right side include Handshake Context and therefore can be used to derive working keys without additional context.",
            "Adjusted": "The key derivation schedule is: PSK -> HKDF-Extract = Early Secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"ext binder\" or \"res binder\", \"\") = binder_key -> Derive-Secret(., \"c e traffic\", ClientHello) = client_early_traffic_secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"e exp master\", ClientHello) = early_exporter_master_secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"derived\", \"\") -> (EC)DHE -> HKDF-Extract = Handshake Secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"c hs traffic\", ClientHello...ServerHello) = client_handshake_traffic_secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"s hs traffic\", ClientHello...ServerHello) = server_handshake_traffic_secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"derived\", \"\") -> 0 -> HKDF-Extract = Master Secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"c ap traffic\", ClientHello...server Finished) = client_application_traffic_secret_0 -> Derive-Secret(., \"s ap traffic\", ClientHello...server Finished) = server_application_traffic_secret_0 -> Derive-Secret(., \"exp master\", ClientHello...server Finished) = exporter_master_secret -> Derive-Secret(., \"res master\", ClientHello...client Finished) = resumption_master_secret. The general pattern here is that the secrets shown down the left side of the diagram are just raw entropy without context, whereas the secrets down the right side include Handshake Context and therefore can be used to derive working keys without additional context."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the different calls to Derive-Secret may take different Messages arguments, even with the same secret.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a 0-RTT exchange, Derive-Secret is called with four distinct transcripts; in a 1-RTT-only exchange, it is called with three distinct transcripts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a given secret is not available, then the 0-value consisting of a string of Hash.length bytes set to zeros is used.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that this does not mean skipping rounds, so if PSK is not in use, Early Secret will still be HKDF-Extract(0, 0).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For the computation of the binder_key, the label is \"ext binder\" for external PSKs (those provisioned outside of TLS) and \"res binder\" for resumption PSKs (those provisioned as the resumption master secret of a previous handshake).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The different labels prevent the substitution of one type of PSK for the other.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There are multiple potential Early Secret values, depending on which PSK the server ultimately selects.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client will need to compute one for each potential PSK; if no PSK is selected, it will then need to compute the Early Secret corresponding to the zero PSK.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once all the values which are to be derived from a given secret have been computed, that secret SHOULD be erased.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.3. Proto:
{
    "9. Compliance Requirements -> 9.3. Protocol Invariants": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes invariants that TLS endpoints and middleboxes MUST follow.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It also applies to earlier versions of TLS.",
            "Adjusted": "These invariants also apply to earlier versions of TLS."
        },
        {
            "Original": "TLS is designed to be securely and compatibly extensible.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Newer clients or servers, when communicating with newer peers, should negotiate the most preferred common parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The TLS handshake provides downgrade protection: Middleboxes passing traffic between a newer client and newer server without terminating TLS should be unable to influence the handshake (seeAppendix E.1).",
            "Adjusted": "The TLS handshake provides downgrade protection: Middleboxes passing traffic between a newer client and newer server without terminating TLS should be unable to influence the handshake (see Appendix E.1)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "At the same time, deployments update at different rates, so a newer client or server MAY continue to support older parameters, which would allow it to interoperate with older endpoints.",
